<FIRST>r a PM-Lites     04-30 0749</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lites,0778</SECOND>
<HEAD>On the Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In true urban cowboy fashion, police
officers in the West are taking to the streets on mountain bikes to
combat crime.
   ``We've found (bikes) to be quite the urban crime fighter,''
said Officer Paul Grady.
   Grady and his partner, Pete Rossen, pioneered the use of bikes
two years ago. As of June 1, Grady said 20 Seattle officers will be
on two-wheelers rather than behind the wheel of a patrol car.
   ``You see (criminals) at the end of an alley, and they disappear
before you can always get to them. We thought of using bikes when
it seemed there just had to be a way to get at them faster,'' Grady
said. ``And on a bike, criminals don't know when or where you might
appear on your beat.''
   Others apparently agree. Police departments in Los Angeles, San
Diego, Palo Alto, Calif., Fort Worth, Texas, Olympia, Wash., and
Victoria, British Columbia have started their own bike detachments.
   Seattle's bikers wear a modified police uniform, including
uniform pants made into bike shorts with a padded seat, a helmet,
bike gloves, a nylon gunbelt and protective glasses, Grady said.
   The idea is a money-saver. The start-up cost is about $1,000 per
officer, and equipping Seattle's 20-man unit cost less than two
squad cars, he said.
   Only one serious injury has occurred so far. One officer broke a
leg during a fight with a felon when he was knocked over his parked
bike, Grady said.
   Lt. Paul Wooten of the Tacoma police said his department plans
to put two officers on bikes in the downtown area later this month.
   ``The officers will be able to ride up and down stairs, over sky
bridges and through parking garages. Boy, when you see an officer
coming at you on a bike you won't forget it,'' said Wooten.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CAMBRIDGE, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As far as members of the Grand National
Waterfowl Hunt Club are concerned, life really does imitate art.
   The club has planned to erect an $80,000 bronze sculpture
``Geese in Flight'' atop a 15-foot obelisk on the banks of the
Choptank River.
   But a pair of migrating osprey got there first. The birds
returned to their summer breeding habitat last month and found the
perch to be an ideal nesting site. For the past several days, the
pair has been carefully arranging branches, twigs and weeds on top
of the pedestal as if planning on a long stay.
   ``If they decide to nest up there, I don't know what will
happen,'' said John W. Tieder Jr., one of the organizers of the
project.
   Sculptor George Northnup had been expected to journey from his
Wyoming home in next few weeks to erect the sculpture, Tieder said.
   The club's problem is how to evict the unwanted guests, and its
plight isn't unique.
   Glenn Therres of the Maryland Forest, Park and Wildlife Service
said the agency has received numerous calls recently asking for
advice on ospreys nesting on piers, light poles and other
inconvenient places.
   ``If nest building has just gotten started, we do authorize
removal of nests,'' Therres said. Approval must come from the state
or the federal Fish and Wildlife Service, though, and nests cannot
be removed after eggs have been laid, he said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WALL TOWNSHIP, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A businessman has come up with a
novel way to celebrate this week's 14th-annual clean air week.
   He's declared today as The Great American Smut Out, part of his
one-man crusade against public profanity.
   ``We have the option of turning off the TV or turning off the
radio or not to see a movie or to close a book that contains foul
language,'' says Bradford Honigsberg. ``We do not have the option
of turning off the people next to us in the restaurant.''
   Honigsberg's previous efforts to improve the quality of life in
the United States included the offering of a $10,000 reward for
information leading to the conviction of medical waste dumpers,
whose trash polluted New Jersey coasts last summer, and an offer of
$10,000 to any U.S. congressman who sponsored legislation making it
illegal to use foul language in a public building.
   The Smut Out seeks to take advantage of a New Jersey law that
outlaws obscene ``public communication.''
   ``I'm the first to enjoy a nice juicy curse word in a card game
... or when I hit my thumb with a hammer,'' Honigsberg said, but
obscenities are inappropriate in public.
</TEXT>
