<FIRST>r e PM-Opera     04-30 0646</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Opera,0661</SECOND>
<HEAD>Met Presents One-Week Ring Cycle for First Time in 50 Years</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE SILVERMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dwarfs, dragons and demigods who populate
Richard Wagner's ring cycle returned to the stage of the
Metropolitan Opera last week true to the composer's wishes for the
first time in 50 years.
   A standing-room-only crowd of nearly 4,000 people paid up to
$620 to see the epic performed the way Wagner wanted it _ all four
operas, totaling 17 hours of music, unfolding in a single week.
   Not since the season of 1938-39 had the Met done the Ring right,
although the individual operas have been performed many times over
the years.
   The Met's new production, already reviled as reactionary by some
critics as they watched it assembled over the last 2{ years, shuns
the current vogue of squeezing Wagner's untidy mythmaking into a
political, economic or psychological mold.
   Instead, the staging by Otto Schenk and sets and costumes by
Guenther Schneider-Siemssen are deliberately old-fashioned, a
throwback to productions that let the drama and music speak for
themselves.
   Scenes and characters are just what they appear to be in this
version of Wagner's tangled tale about the theft of a golden ring
and the disasters that befall all who pursue it.
   The Rhinemaidens are really mermaids, not prostitutes as in one
production, and their river is not a hydroelectric dam; Wotan is
really the king of the gods, not a 19th century capitalist;
Siegfried is really a noble young warrior, not a garage mechanic.
   With no striking interpretation to hold the audience's interest,
the production might fall flat if the singing and orchestral
playing were not on such a high level.
   The orchestra sounded splendid all week and conductor James
Levine kept things moving with a keen sense of dramatic tension.
Aside from a wobbly horn here or there and a rare sour note, the
sound was as close to perfection as any orchestra could produce.
   Hildegard Behrens once again proved herself the finest Wagnerian
performer of her generation. Though she lacks the vocal power of a
Flagstad or a Nilsson, she makes up for that with dramatic
intensity. And she looks the part of a beautiful young Valkyrie _
this was no case of the opera being over when the fat lady sings.
   Bass James Morris was a superior Wotan, his brilliant high notes
cutting through the heavy orchestration with ease. Another
outstanding bass, Matti Salminen, carried off the rare feat of
appearing in all four operas, as Fafner (a giant in ``Das
Rheingold'' but transformed into a dragon in ``Siegfried''); as
Hunding in ``Die Walkuere,'' and as Hagen in ``Goetterdaemmerung.''
   Other singers who made memorable contributions to the week
included Franz Mazura and Graham Clark as the brother dwarfs
Alberich and Mime; Helga Dernesch as Wotan's nagging wife Fricka
(but not as Waltraute in ``Goetterdaemmrung'' where the high notes
were too much for her); Siegfried Jerusalem as the crafty god Loge,
Brigitta Svenden as the prophetess Erda and Mari-Anne Haeggender,
unusually sweet-sounding as the goddess Freia.
   As the romantic lovers Siegmund and Sieglinde, Robert Schunk and
Ellen Shade looked convincing and sang acceptably but were no vocal
match for the team that appeared in earlier performances, Gary
Lakes and Jessye Norman.
   A bigger problem was the Siegfried of Toni Kraemer. He acted
fairly well, but had to press his voice in the upper register and
tired under the heavy demands of his role. The world is still
waiting for a true heldentenor who can do justice to this killer
role.
   The Met is offering one more ``Ring Cycle'' this week, with
Gwyneth Jones as Bruennhilde, William Johns as Siegfried and Hans
Sotin as Wotan. It will be back three more times next spring, and
will be televised on four consecutive nights in June 1990 by the
Public Broadcasting Service.
</TEXT>
