<FIRST>r a AM-Obit-Adams     04-30 0270</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Obit-Adams,0278</SECOND>
<HEAD>Man Who Rescued Bush During World War II</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ralph E. Adams, a World War II submariner who
helped rescue a downed flyer destined to become president of the
United States, has died at age 76.
   Adams died at his home of cancer on April 21.
   He was part of a rescue party sent from the USS Finback on Sept.
4, 1944, to pick up then Lt. j.g. George Bush and four other downed
Navy airmen in a rubber raft bobbing about 70 miles off Osaka,
Japan.
   ``I was one of the four men in our `man overboard party' that
went for them,'' Adams said in a November 1988 interview. ``I was
in the party because I was the best swimmer.''
   Bush, who had been piloting a single-engine bomber that was shot
down by the Japanese, and one of his crewmen were in the raft along
with three other flyers from another downed plane.
   ``I think that Bush and the others were suprised that they were
going to have to stay with us so long,'' Adams said. ``I think they
thought we'd take them right back to their (aircraft) carrier or
right to some American base. But our orders were to stay at sea, on
lifeguard duty, for another 30 days.''
   Bush and the other survivors stayed aboard the Finback until the
submarine reached Midway Island around Oct. 15, 1944, Adams said.
   Adams, a native of Crete, Ill., served in the Navy from 1929
until 1933. He rejoined in 1940 and retired as a chief petty
officer in 1970.
   Funeral services were scheduled for Wednesday.
</TEXT>
