<FIRST>r a AM-StealthBomber     04-30 0320</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Stealth Bomber,0331</SECOND>
<HEAD>B-2 Represents Quantum Leap in Technology, Air Force General Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ARTHUR H. ROTSTEIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SCOTTSDALE, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three or four B-2 Stealth bombers could
have handled the 1986 Libyan bombing raid better than the nearly
100 planes that carried out the raid, a high-ranking Air Force
official said Saturday.
   ``We're talking about an airplane that just gives us much more
flexibility than anything right now in the strategic deterrent
family,'' said Gen. Bernard S. Randolph, commander of the Air Force
Systems Command.
   If the B-2 had been in the Air Force arsenal three years ago,
three or four flying from the United States and refueling en route
could have bombed Libya with complete surprise, more efficiency and
accuracy than the European-based planes that did the job, he said.
   Randolph addressed the annual news conference of the
Aviation-Space Writers Association.
   The bomber can carry up to 80 500-pound conventional bombs or 20
nuclear weapons, can fly from low levels to altitudes of about
50,000 feet and personifies a technological leap into the next
century, he said.
   The subsonic two-man aircraft will weigh more than 350,000
pounds with weapons and fuel and have a range of more than 6,000
nautical miles, or more than 10,000 with one refueling, Randolph
said.
   The range is greater than that of a B-52, the mainstay of the
nation's bomber fleet for three decades, he said. The plane will be
able to fly from any airfield that can handle a Boeing 727, he said.
   With two domestic and two overseas bases, the United States will
be able to attack any land mass in the world, Randolph said.
   The B-2 is scheduled to make its first flight this summer.
   Last week, Defense Secretary Richard Cheney said the
administration would delay purchasing the plane pending a review of
the program, which has been estimated to cost $70 billion for 132
planes.
</TEXT>
