<FIRST>r a AM-Deaths 1stLd-Writethru a0580 04-30 0664</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Deaths, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0580,0685</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: AMs separates moved as a0574 on Yeutter and a0540 on Geronimi,
a0604 on Adams, a0598 on Frosch, a0593 on Deskey.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Laura Yeutter</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COZAD, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Laura P. Yeutter, mother of U.S. Agriculture
Secretary Clayton Yeutter, who grew up on a Nebraska farm and was
known for her passion for roses, died Thursday. She was 92.
   Mrs. Yeutter was known to many as the ``Rose Lady'' because of
her 30 rose bushes at her home.
   Mrs. Yeutter, born on Feb. 21, 1897, was raised on a Nebraska
farm and was married in 1923 to Reinold ``Doc'' Yeutter. They lived
on a farm between Eustis and Cozad until her husband's death in
1965, when she moved to Cozad.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Clyde Geronimi</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWPORT BEACH, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Academy Award-winning animator
Clyde ``Gerry'' Geronimi, who worked on such classic Walt Disney
films as ``Cinderella'' and ``Sleeping Beauty'' in a 28-year career
for the studio, died Monday. He was 87.
   Before joining Disney in 1931, Geronimi worked at Hearst
studios. In 1939 he won his first Oscar for the cartoon short ``The
Ugly Duckling.'' He captured his second Oscar in 1942 for another
short, ``Lend a Paw.''
   Geronimi also worked as a segment director on such Disney films
as ``The Three Caballeros,'' and ``Peter Pan,'' and was supervising
director on ``101 Dalmatians.''
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Eric Nord</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN JOSE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eric ``Big Daddy'' Nord, the 6-foot-8,
400-pound founder of the hungry i nightspot in San Francisco, died
Wednesday after several years of failing health. He was 69.
   Born Harry Pastor to a German industrialist and his American
wife, Nord's family came to California and he quickly became
involved in the beat culture and places like the Co-Existence Bagel
Shop.
   Nord opened the hungry i in 1950 and helped further the careers
of such rebellious satirists as Lenny Bruce and Mort Sahl.
   ``Big Daddy'' spent his later years in Los Gatos, sometimes
playing Santa at Christmas for local hospitals.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Ralph Adams</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ralph E. Adams, a World War II submariner who
helped rescue a downed Navy flyer destined to become president of
the United States, died April 21 of cancer. He was 76.
   He was part of a rescue party sent from the USS Finback on Sept.
4, 1944, to pick up then Lt. j.g. George Bush and four other downed
Navy airmen in a rubber raft bobbing about 70 miles off Osaka,
Japan.
   Bush, who had been piloting a single-engine bomber that was shot
down by the Japanese, and one of his crewmen were in the raft along
with three other flyers from another downed plane.
   Adams, a native of Crete, Ill., served in the Navy from 1929
until 1933. He rejoined in 1940 and retired as a chief petty
officer in 1970.
