<BYLINE>Donald Deskey</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VERO BEACH, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Donald Deskey, an innovative industrial
designer whose credits range from the interiors of New York's Radio
City Music Hall to the Crest toothpaste package, died Saturday of
pneumonia. He was 94.
   Deskey, whose career spanned more than half a century, was
associated with the Procter and Gamble Co. for 20 years. His design
for Crest toothpaste has not changed since its introduction in the
1950s.
   An adept interior designer as well, he created apartments for
such prominent Abby Aldrich Rockefeller in 1929 and Helena
Rubinstein in 1930. His 1932 designs for Radio City's interiors are
hailed as Art Deco masterpieces.
   Born in Blue Earth, Minn., Deskey had homes in Scotland, Jamaica
and Florida as well as an apartment in Manhattan. He retired to
Vero Beach in 1975.
