<HEAD>Acclaimed Director of Spaghetti Westerns Dead at 60</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sergio Leone, a critically acclaimed director of
spaghetti westerns, died early Sunday morning, Italian state radio
reported. He was 60.
   Leone died of a heart attack at home, according to the radio and
the Italian news agency ANSA.
   The director's credits included ``The Good, the Bad and the
Ugly'' and ``A Fistful of Dollars.''
   Leone began his film career as an assistant on Vittorio De
Sica's ``Bicycle Thief,'' and worked on the popular epic films made
in Rome in the 1950s that included ``Ben Hur'' and ``The Last Days
of Pompeii.''
   He went on to direct a series of stylish, often violent,
westerns that were smashes at the box office and also won him
critical recognition. They included ``For A Few Dollars More,''
``Once Upon a Time in the West'' and ``Duck You Sucker.''
   Leone established his own production company in Rome but later
made his home in Italy and in France.
