<FIRST>r i AM-France-PLO     04-30 0472</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-France-PLO,0486</SECOND>
<HEAD>French Jews Protest Arafat Visit</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARILYN AUGUST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jewish leaders are protesting PLO leader Yasser
Arafat's visit to Paris this week and calling for silent vigils to
honor victims of terrorism.
   The Palestine Liberation Organization leader is to arrive
Tuesday morning for a two-day visit, beginning with talks at the
Elysee Palace with President Francois Mitterrand.
   The Representative Council of Jewish Institutions appealed to
the French to turn out in large numbers Monday evening at Jo
Goldenberg's restaurant in Paris.
   Terrorists burst into the popular Jewish restaurant in August
1982, spraying machine-gun bullets that killed six, including two
Americans, and injured 21.
   Vigils also were planned at the Tati department store, where a
bomb hurled from a passing car killed seven people and injured 51
in September 1986; and at the Point Show shopping gallery on the
Champs Elysees, the site of a terrorist bombing in March 1986 that
killed two and injured 28.
   The largest demonstration is expected Tuesday in front of the
Copernic synagogue, where in October 1980 a bomb killed four.
   The attacks on Goldenberg's restaurant and the Copernic
synagogue are believed to have been carried out by the Abu Nidal
organization or another Palestinian splinter group opposed to the
PLO. The Tati and Point Show bombings are thought to have been the
work of pro-Iranian Lebanese terrorists.
   Theo Klein, head of the Reprsentative Council of Jewish
Institutions, said all victims of terrorism would be memorialized
by the demonstrations, including Arab leaders who believed in an
Israeli-Palestinian dialogue and who were killed because of their
views.
   Klein denounced the Arafat visit.
   ``I'm sorry no one has thought it useful to mention on the
occasion of this visit that terrorism exists, that the Jewish
community has been its target, that the PLO is responsible in part
for the terrorism and that it is up to the Jewish community to say
so,'' Klein said in a statement.
   Klein said French Jews find the visit especially offensive
because it coincides with Yom Ha-Shoah, the day marking the Nazi
extermination of millions of Jews.
   On Thursday, Mitterrand wrote to Klein trying to ease the anger
of the Jewish community.
   ``Beyond the present circumstances, France has not forgotten the
victims of the Shoah, nor those of blind terrorism,'' Mitterrand
wrote, using the Hebrew word for the Holocaust.
   ``This cruel and cowardly past is not erased from our memories
as we conduct French foreign policy. But it is founded on dialogue,
which makes it necessary to hear both sides. To hear is not to
approve.''
   While many Jews say it is inappropriate for Mitterrand to meet
with Arafat, some have expressed hope it will further the cause of
peace in the Middle East.
   Arafat on Wednesday is to meet with Premier Michel Rocard and
tour the Louvre.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
