<SECOND>AM-Japan-Ship Deaths,0249</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two Dead, Four Missing When Lifeboat Sinks Near Leaking Freighter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A lifeboat capsized in rough seas Sunday as it
carried crew members from a leaking Peruvian cargo ship, and two
people died and four were missing, the coast guard said.
   The lifeboat was carrying 10 of the 26 Peruvian crew members of
the 6,896-ton Yacuwasi when it overturned in the Pacific Ocean
about 638 miles east of Sendai in northern Japan, according to the
Maritime Safety Agency.
   The lifeboat was attempting to shuttle crew members to the
nearby Japanese freighter Kyokushin-maru, an agency official said,
speaking on condition of anonymity.
   Six of the crew members in the lifeboat were picked up by the
Japanese vessel, but one was dead and another died about an hour
later, the agency said.
   Four crew members were lost.
   The official said the 16 other crew members remained aboard the
Yacuwasi, which was taking on water.
   The Yacuwasi, owned by Naviera Anazonica of Peru, was traveling
from Peru to Aomori in northern Japan with a cargo of copper ore
when it began leaking, the official said.
   The official said the Maritime Safety Agency was sending two
Japanese patrol boats that would reach the scene Monday.
   Yutaka Mifune, a Maritime Safety official, said the Peruvian
cargo ship was in rough seas that may have caused damage to the
hull, but he said the cause of the leak was still unknown.
