<FIRST>r w AM-CongressRdp     04-30 0703</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Congress Rdp,700</SECOND>
<HEAD>As Congress Readies 1990 Deficit Cuts, Urge to Spend Is Still Strong</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House and Senate are set to move closer
next week to enacting a deficit-reduction package for fiscal 1990,
but lawmakers have shown again that it is still spending that
drives many of Congress' decisions.
   The Senate plans to begin debate on Tuesday on a $1.16 trillion
spending plan, and the House is scheduled to consider its $1.17
trillion version the next day. Leaders of both chambers expect the
measures to be approved, and are hoping that a compromise plan can
be completed by mid-May.
   The two packages each claim to whittle this year's expected
federal deficit of $163 billion to just above $99 billion for 1990,
using a recipe of spending cuts, new revenues, sunny economic
assumptions and accounting gimmicks.
   The outlines of the savings were drawn in a pact reached last
month between President Bush and congressional leaders of both
parties, an alliance that makes ultimate approval of the budget
likely.
   In other congressional activity, a group of Texas investors in a
gas well venture have been subpoenaed to appear Wednesday and
Thursday before the House ethics committee, which is continuing its
probe of the personal finances of House Speaker Jim Wright, D-Texas.
   The witnesses refused to speak to members of the panel last week
when they tried to interview them in San Antonio, Texas.
   The House may vote on whether to impeach a U.S. district judge
from Mississippi, Walter L. Nixon, who is serving five years in
prison for a perjury conviction. Nixon is hoping to return to the
bench when his prison term is up.
   Congress' budget votes next week will be greeted by lawmakers
who will praise the deficit-reduction plans as healthy first steps
toward steeper budget cutting in the future. But there is a
contrast between those sentiments and some that were expressed in
the House last week during Congress' first major budget vote of the
year.
   Last Wednesday, the House rejected a plan by its Democratic
leaders that would have paid for a $4.7 billion spending bill for
this year by slashing defense, domestic and foreign aid programs.
   Some lawmakers voted against the measure because they said they
wanted it cut down in size. Others, however, took to the floor to
make it clear that they opposed the spending reductions it
contained, cuts that happened to affect programs they are connected
to.
   Rep. William Natcher, D-Ky., who chairs the Appropriations
health and education subcommittee, warned, ``If you take care of
the health of your people and educate your children, you can
continue living in the strongest country in the world.''
   Moments later, Rep. Beverly Byron, D-Md., told her colleagues
that the cuts would have a ``devastating impact'' on ``our men and
women in uniform.'' Byron chairs the Armed Services military
personnel subcommittee.
   House Minority Whip Newt Gingrich, R-Ga., went even further,
saying the legislation ``basically says we can get to a balanced
budget if only we abolish the Defense Department.''
   In the end, the vote against the proposal was 252-172, with 92
Democrats voting against their own leadership.
   ``That vote was not an expression of deficit reduction
mentality,'' said Rep. Bill Schuette, R-Mich., a Budget Committee
member who voted for the plan. ``It was a coalition of people who
didn't want further cuts in defense, and people who didn't want
other programs cut.''
   How is that sentiment likely to effect this week's budget votes?
   The conventional wisdom among many lawmakers is that if
anything, it will help the leaders obtain passage of the budget
resolutions. Many domestic programs are slated for spending
increases, and the defense cuts have the endorsement of the Bush
administration.
   That's not to say there won't be some rebellions. Rep. G.V.
Sonny Montgomery, D-Ala., chairman of the House Veterans Affairs
Committee, said Friday he would lead a fight to seek $300 million
more for veterans hospitals.
   ``If they don't give us the money, they shouldn't come around
when the secretary says he has to close some units,'' said
Montgomery, who said he had not decided what he would do if he
could not obtain the extra funds.
</TEXT>
