<FILEID>AP-NR-04-30-89 1146EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-FalseClaims     04-30 0838</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-False Claims,850</SECOND>
<HEAD>Civil War-Era Law Produces Flood Of New Cases</HEAD>
<BYLINE>BY JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Civil War-era law allowing citizens to bring
fraud suits against government contractors has produced a flood of
new cases despite doubts about its cost-effectiveness and its
constitutionality.
   The False Claims Act was first passed by Congress in 1863 after
Union commanders found they had been cheated by munitions makers
who sold them bullets filled with sawdust.
   For 123 years, citizens made little use of the so-called ``qui
tam'' provisions _ legal shorthand for a longer Latin phrase
meaning ``Who, as well as for the king as for himself, sues in this
matter.''
   But in 1986, Congress passed amendments giving citizens a
financial incentive to come forward with allegations of wrongdoing.
Citizens can share between 15 percent and 30 percent of the
judgment if the government wins the case.
   ``This law gave me the incentive to do what I should have done
anyway,'' said Christopher Urda, a former bids administrator for a
defense contractor who has brought one of the biggest suits to date.
   The government recently decided to intervene and become the lead
plaintiff in Urda's $231 million suit charging that Singer Co.'s
Link Flight Simulation unit had fraudulently overcharged the
government for flight simulator equipment for eight years.
   In the last three years, more than 140 cases have been filed in
federal courts, mostly against defense contractors.
   After a case is filed under court seal, the government has 60
days to decide whether to intervene and take over the litigation
   So far, the Justice Department has entered 20 cases and declined
to join 60 others. The rest remain under court seal pending Justice
Department review.
   Department officials question whether the financial recoveries
from the suits will be worth the time government lawyers must spend
evaluating the complaints.
   Some lawyers in and out of the department have questioned the
constitionality of allowing private citizens to bring civil cases
on behalf of the government.
   The Justice Department is now deciding whether to take a
position on constitutional challenges to the law being mounted by
defense contractors who were sued. Because the law was to little
used until 1986, its constitutionality was never challenged
previously in the courts.
   The department declined to take a position on a case involving
McDonnell Douglas Corp. now pending in federal court in Los Angeles.
   But Washington attorney Richard Sauber, a former government
prosecutor, says the government is studying whether to support
constitutional challenges he is mounting for Northrop Corp.
   The law is unconstitutional, Sauber argues, because ``it gives
to private parties a law enforcement function and the right to sue
on behalf of the United States.''
   Continued use of the law by private plaintiffs means the
government ``is going to be saddled with the lawyering and the
legal strategy'' begun by private citizens, he said.
   If a private plaintiff loses a suit, the government could be
foreclosed from bringing a new case if it found better evidence of
fraud, he said.
   ``What if they investigate it and decide not to come in?''
Sauber said. ``The private people get a hold of it and muck it up.
But six months later they have new evidence?''
   The 1986 amendments were enacted by Congress in the wake concern
about waste in defense procurement, including revelations that the
Pentagon had paid $600 for a toilet seat and $7,400 for a coffee
pot.
   ``With major dollars going to the defense budget, people wanted
it to be properly spent,'' said Stuart E. Schiffer, a deputy
assistant attorney general who oversees the law's enforcement.
   The amendment passed despite misgivings in the Justice
Department about whether the long-dormant law should be revived.
   The department ``had a policy concern about whether or not it
was really needed and surely it had constitutional dimensions _
that the attorney general should be in charge of bringing a suit to
vindicate the public interest,'' Schiffer said.
   The 60-day review requirement has imposed ``very severe'' time
constraints on the commercial fraud section of the Justice
Department, Schiffer said.
   ``It obviously means we're not able to take the cases in the
order we would take cases,'' Schiffer said.
   Michael Hertz, who heads the commercial fraud section, said a
study he conducted showed his staff of 40 attorneys has spent about
25 percent of its time reviewing False Claims suits.
   In the period of time Hertz reviewed, False Claims Act suits
generated between $5 and $10 million for the government compared
with $175 million produced by cases developed by federal
investigators.
   ``You get some idea of the amount of resources going to qui tam
cases versus the payoff,'' Hertz said.
   Recently, the government has intervened in some large cases that
have the potential of big settlements.
   Other big cases will probably increase the returns to the
Treasury from the ``qui tam'' provision, but ``whether it is going
to come up to the level of justifying spending all the time on it I
have no idea,'' Hertz said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890430-0019 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-30-89 1145EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--ShipRescue     04-30 0170</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Ship Rescue,0172</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ship Sinks Off Namibia, All 20 Crewmen Saved</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAPE TOWN, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A ship carrying timber sank in
rough seas, but all 20 crewmen were rescued when a South African
helicopter and an Israeli vessel teamed up to find the seamen's
lifeboat, an official said Sunday.
   The bulk carrier Sevasti sank Saturday about 115 miles west of
Luderitz, Namibia, and its Greek crew entered a life raft and
radioed for help, said Maj. Flories Brand, a spokesman at the South
African Sea and Rescue Center.
   An Air Force Dakota helicopter was sent to search for the raft
and radioed ships in the area to watch for the men. Contact with
the lifeboat was later lost, probably because the radio's batteries
ran low, Brand said.
   On Saturday night, the Israeli vessel Azgad 4 found the life
raft and picked up all 20 crew members, said Brand. He quoted the
survivors as saying the ship listed when its cargo shifted, then
sank about two hours later.
</TEXT>
