<HEAD>Yi Bang-ja, Widow Of Korean Prince, Dies At 88</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Yi Bang-ja, a member of Japan's royal
family who married the late Korean prince Yi Un, died Sunday. She
was 88.
   Family members said Mrs. Yi, who was being treated for
phlebitis, died shortly after being moved from Seoul National
Hospital to Changduk Palace.
   She will be buried at a royal graveyard outside Seoul on May 8,
they said.
   Mrs. Yi, a Japanese royal family member, married Prince Yi Un, a
son of King Kojong, in Tokyo in 1920, 10 years after Japan annexed
the Korean peninsula as its colony. The prince died in 1970.
   Mrs. Yi, whose Japanese name is Masako, became a naturalized
Korean citizen in 1945 after World War II. She devoted herself to
charitable activities, such as setting up a nursing home for the
handicapped.
   She was a cousin of Japanese Empress Dowager Nagako, widow of
Emperor Hirohito, who died in January. She also was the eldest
daughter of Morimasa and Itsuko Nashimoto, then imperial family
members.
