<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Iran-Drugs     04-30 0158</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Iran-Drugs,0161</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ten Drug Smugglers Hanged in Iran</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ten drug traffickers were hanged Sunday
in the Iranian capital, Tehran, and in three other cities,
state-run Tehran radio reported.
   The radio, monitored in Nicosia, said the men had smuggled and
distributed more than 1,058 pounds of narcotics. Some also were
convicted of theft and embezzlement, the report said.
   The Islamic Republic News Agency, also monitored in Nicosia,
reported that two men were hanged in Tehran, one in the nearby city
of Varamin, four in Rasht in northern Gilan Province, and three in
Arak in central Markazi Province.
   The hangings brought to 516 the total number of executions since
tough new drug laws that took effect Jan. 21. The law mandates the
death sentence for possession of even small quantities of drugs.
   Many arrests have been in provinces along the border with
Pakistan and Afghanistan, from where authorities say most drugs are
smuggled into Iran.
