<DOCNO> AP890430-0023 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-30-89 1206EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-BaseClosing-Chanute     04-30 0690</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Base Closing-Chanute,0713</SECOND>
<HEAD>Town Braces For Loss Of Air Force Base, Jobs, Money</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Gery is cq in 5th graf</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT LEE ZIMMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RANTOUL, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 1931 photograph on a wall at the
headquarters at the Air Force's Chanute Technical Training Center
shows a soldier dangling from a biplane, his parachute caught on
its tail.
   Residents of this central Illinois town _ where nearly half the
people and two-thirds of the economy are associated with the base _
feel they, too, are dangling because the base is one of 86 Congress
voted to close.
   Mayor Katy Podagrosi said it could take two years to exhaust
efforts in the courts and in Congress to remove Chanute from the
list.
   ``That's not long when the stakes are as high as they are,''
said Podagrosi.
   ``The big problem is the uncertainty,'' said Al Vogelsang, owner
of Gery &amp; Al's Sporting Goods. ``Will it actually close, how long
will it take for them to leave and how soon can we get something in
there to take Chanute's place?''
   The House voted 381-43 on April 18 to reject a resolution to
disapprove the recommendations of the Base Closure and Realignment
Commission.
   That meant the recommendations now goes into effect, giving
Defense Secretary Dick Cheney the go-ahead to implement the
recommendations beginning in January. The law creating the
commission required that the entire package take effect unless both
houses of Congress voted to disapprove it.
   The Pentagon contends the closings will save taxpayers $693
million a year.
   But residents hope a judge will agree that the commission's
report included misleading information about Chanute.
   Illinois congressmen have argued that transcripts of commission
deliberations have shown that discussions about Chanute involved
figures and reports that were more than a decade old.
   Commission members acknowledged they invented property values at
Chanute, creating unrealistic estimates of savings. They also
referred to Chanute as ``an empty air base,'' despite 51 training
programs that graduate 24,000 students a year. Several members
disclosed they didn't know where the base was.
   Chanute, now one of five Air Force technical training centers,
opened in 1917 and reached its peak during World War II, training
more than 200,000 soldiers.
   The 2,400-acre base, located within the Rantoul city limits, has
239 buildings, 1,473 family housing units and dormitories for 5,879
servicemen.
   There are about 3,000 students, 3,100 regular military personnel
and 2,400 civilian workers. The annual payroll, including retired
servicemen living in the area, is $169 million.
   Illinois congressmen hope to block the closing through the
appropriations process. Congress still must appropriate the money
for short-term expenses associated with closing the bases.
   Critics of closing note that the government has spent $42.2
million in the last five years on new or improved facilities at
Chanute.
   Sen. Alan Dixon, D-Ill., examined a nearly complete $6.5 million
military weather school and a partially constructed $4.6 million
officers' dormitory last week, saying, ``Somebody in Washington has
to be very stupid to close this base before anyone lives in it.''
   ``Everybody here will go somewhere else, and they'll have to
reproduce all of these facilities at another base,'' said Dixon.
   Podagrosi said closure would mean loss of 65 percent of the
town's economic activity, along with about 8,000 of its 20,000
residents.
   A University of Illinois study estimated one-third of the 3,075
single-family homes would be for sale, and that property values
would drop 20 percent.
   The loss of Chanute also would create hardships for about 5,000
retired military people who count on free medical care and
prescriptions on base as well as reduced prices in base stores.
   Frank Elliott, economic development director for Rantoul, said
there are other options for the base, such as industries or schools.
   ``We haven't given up the cause yet, but we're looking at these
other possibilities,'' said Elliott.
   Residents hope Chanute will stay open so Rantoul's ordeal ends
as happily as the dangling paratrooper's predicament ended 58 years
ago.
   A fellow airman walked out on the wing of a second plane and
lowered a knife to the young man, who then cut himself free and
floated to safety.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
