<HEAD>Fire At Japanese Factory Kills One Person</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A fire at a factory and a workers' dormitory killed
one person Sunday and left more than 40 people homeless,
authorities said.
   The fire started about 2:30 a.m. in the main factory building of
the Shinko Spinning Co. in Sennan City, a suburb of Osaka, 255
miles west of Tokyo, and it spread to a warehouse and employee
dormitory because of strong winds.
   One factory worker was killed, but 16 other employees working
the night shift escaped. Forty-two people living in the dormitory
were left homeless.
   About 60 people living nearby were evacuated, but fire officials
confined the fire to the three buildings of the factory compound,
which was heavily damaged. An investigation into the cause of the
fire was in progress.
