<FIRST>r i AM-China-Dissident     04-30 0635</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-Dissident,0660</SECOND>
<HEAD>Wife, Daughter See Jailed Husband After Three Years</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN POMFRET</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The wife and daughter of one of China's most
prominent imprisoned dissidents were allowed to visit him in jail
Sunday for the first time in more than three years.
   Kan Tong and her daughter, Xu Jin, said they visited Xu Wenli
for 30 minutes at Beijing's No. 1 Prison. They were accompanied by
five police officers and one stenographer who scribbled what they
said in a small blue book.
   Police told them not to touch Xu, who was sentenced in 1981 to
15 years in jail for counterrevolutionary crimes. They said
authorities refused Xu's request to kiss his 16-year-old daughter.
   At the end of the meeting, Kan defied the order and shook her
husband's hand.
   ``It was cold and dry,'' she said. ``His hand was shaking.''
   She said her husband had turned into ``a bag of bones.''
   ``His hair is completely white and all the teeth on the left
side of his mouth have fallen out.''
   ``He is this thin,'' said Xu Jin, holding up one of her fragile
arms. ``I have never seen a man so thin.''
   No family member had been allowed to visit Xu since Oct. 10,
1985, after an essay by Xu, titled ``My Self-Defense,'' was
smuggled out of prison. In it, Xu gave details of his arrest and
prosecution in an account critical of the regime.
   Prison authorities further punished him by moving him from an
86-square-foot room to a 43-square-foot cell, she said, citing his
letters and reports from sources in the jail. Guards took away his
bed and forced him to sleep on bricks. Lights were always on.
   Xu, an electrician by profession, was a leader of the Democracy
Wall movement of 1978 and published an unsanctioned periodical
calling for political change. In the journal,``April 5th Forum,''
which was mimeographed in his home, Xu argued that a multiparty
system was not anti-communist and would help the socialist cause.
   The movement was tolerated by China's new leader, Deng Xiaoping,
until he consolidated power. After that a crackdown came.
   Xu is one of China's most famous dissidents, but his fame is
greater outside China, a testimony to the power of China's
state-run press to limit access to information.
   Most of those currently participating in a Beijing student
movement for democracy and a free press don't know who Xu is.
   Since January a growing number of Chinese intellectuals have
called for the release of political prisoners. The government
denies it has any political prisoners.
   Kan said news of the current pro-democracy protests made her
husband happy.
   ``He may be weak but his spirit is still there,'' she said. ``He
is still Xu Wenli.''
   She said prison officials told her Saturday that a request to
see her husband had been approved.
   ``We hope you can help us educate Xu Wenli,'' read a letter from
the prison. ``Therefore we will consider your request.''
   Recently, Xu's treatment appears to have improved since 1985,
Kan said.
   Throughout the meeting, she had trouble looking at her husband,
she said.
   ``We sat there on benches. The police were on high chairs,
sitting above us. Both of us just looked at our hands. He was
shaking, he shook throughout the meeting. Then he cried.''
   Xu Jin said she only looked at her father once.
   ``I asked him if I was a woman yet,'' she said. ``He said I'm
still a little girl. Then I couldn't look at him anymore. I drank
tea.''
   Kan said prison authorities allowed her to give Xu a bag of
goodies, including his favorite fish dish, sesame oil, hot pepper
oil, and a recent book by Richard Nixon.
   ``Thirty minutes went fast,'' she said. ``I don't know whether
there will be a next time.''
</TEXT>
