<FIRST>r a AM-Brites     04-30 0480</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brites,0497</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bright &amp; Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HUNTINGTON, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A local detective took on a case of a
different sort when he was called in on a bird hunt for a
foul-tempered parrot who flew the coop.
   Armed only with a variety of bird calls, police Detective C.D.
Morrison winged it in his search for Charlie, a $2,000 South
American Macaw parrot who ventured from his perch.
   Charlie's owners, Robert and Chris Mort, notified police after
they discovered the bird was missing Thursday evening.
   ``We let her out on the front porch, she's sort of the
neighborhood watch dog,'' Mrs. Mort said.
   Morrison said he tried to attract the bird by making parrot
calls, but there was no response.
   The Morts on Friday asked meter readers, mail carriers, police
and school children to aid in the search for Charlie.
   Morrison returned with a bird in his hand Friday afternoon after
a neighbor became a stool pigeon and turned Charlie in.
   ``She was about a block away in a big tall tree and a lady over
there spotted her,'' Mrs. Mort said. ``She's okay, just a little
wet.''
   The Morts were concerned not only about the parrot's
disappearance but about her mood swings. Charlie, who likes fried
chicken and coffee, can become very foul tempered for no reason,
they say.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SPOKANE, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A wallaroo that was apparently not in the
mood for mating may have set a new high jump record when it escaped
from the Walk in the Wild Zoo by leaping a 7-foot fence.
   The animal's caretaker, Mike Cassell, said he was putting a
female wallaroo _ a cross between a kangaroo and a wallaby _ inside
a wire enclosure housing a male wallaroo at the zoo when the male
escaped Friday afternoon.
   Cassell, other zoo workers and Spokane County Animal Control
employees searched for the 3-foot-tall, dark gray animal in the
brushy areas along the Spokane River before it was finally cornered
in the front yard of a residence about two miles from the zoo.
   Zookeeper John McLachlan injected the wallaroo with an
anesthetic, but it took four people to pick up the struggling
animal and put it in a truck to be returned to the zoo.
   Cassell was relieved at the successful recovery.
   ``If the animal is stressed bad enough, I've seen them quiver up
and die,'' he said during the chase. ``They're really docile
animals. ... I'm amazed that he would even try to cross the road,
they're that timid.''
   Wallaroos aren't usually so flighty, and Cassell said this was
the first one to ever bolt from the zoo.
   The animal first escaped the wire enclosure and then, after an
emu started chasing it, ``it jumped over the 7-foot fence,''
Cassell said. ``According to the book, it's not able to jump over
four feet. I guess this one never read the book.''
</TEXT>
