<FILEID>AP-NR-04-30-89 1434EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-DrugWarRoom Bjt   04-30 0673</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Drug War Room, Bjt,0690</SECOND>
<HEAD>High-Tech `War Room' Latest Outpost in Drug War</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL WARREN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A ``drug war situation room'' unveiled by President
Bush last week and one like it in California may be the nation's
most sophisticated anti-smuggling weapons yet, but some question
whether such high-tech wizardry can do much.
   Bush dedicated the Customs Service-Coast Guard interdiction
center Thursday during a visit to Miami, where he also addressed
top Latin American drug-fighting officials at an international
conference.
   ``Think of this as one of America's drug war situation rooms, as
our early warning network against narcotics,'' Bush said after
watching a computer simulation of a drug interdiction in which
smugglers were tracked through the skies and seas off Miami and
intercepted by jets and speedboats.
   The Command, Control, Communications and Intelligence Center, or
C3I, is in a squat, peach-colored building southwest of Miami in a
field dotted with radar antennas.
   Information from a network of land, sea and air radar monitored
by the Federal Aviation Administration, Customs, the Coast Guard
and the Pentagon will be displayed on a video system.
   Specialists will compare radar data with FAA flight plans, field
updates and intelligence reports to keep track of up to 5,000 boats
and planes across more than 12 million square miles in the eastern
United States.
   C3I West in Riverside, Calif., has directed air interdiction
west of Houston since August.
   ``My sources within the Defense Department say they don't have
anything to match C3I from a technical standpoint. It's a very
sophisticated system designed specifically for drug interdiction,''
said Rep. Glenn English, D-Okla., former chairman of the House
subcommittee responsible for overseeing the drug war.
   ``There's no better way we could spend this $33 million,'' said
Customs Commissioner William von Raab, standing in front of a
Customs Blackhawk helicopter outside the center Thursday.
   ``We were absolutely defenseless in our air borders. Five years
ago, you could fly anywhere into the United States and not stand a
snowball's chance of getting caught,'' von Raab said. ``Now we are
well out in front of the smugglers and we are never going to fall
behind again.''
   Others aren't so confident. They point to longstanding problems
such as inter-agency rivalry, a lack of equipment such as radar,
planes and boats, and a shortage of intelligence.
   ``You have to recognize you're going up against an entity that
is bringing in $150 billion a year _ roughly half of our total
defense spending _ with $6-7 billion a year from the U.S.
government,'' English said.
   Cocaine seizures, virtually non-existent before the 1980s, are
growing nationwide.
   The Coast Guard hauled in 14,591 pounds in fiscal 1988, up from
12,950 in 1987. Customs seized 138,808 pounds in fiscal 1988,
compared to a combined 140,419 in 1986 and 1987.
   Marijuana seizures by both agencies have dropped sharply in what
officials say is a sign that the law is forcing smugglers to move
to lower risk, higher profit cocaine.
   But authorities intercept at best only about 10 percent of the
3,500 flights and 4,500 boat trips smugglers make each year,
according to the Congressional Office of Technology Assessment.
   Upwards of 18 million pounds of marijuana, 300,000 pounds of
cocaine and 13,000 pounds of heroin will be smuggled into the
country this year, the office estimates.
   Before the C3I center can improve these numbers, gaps in the
radar network must be filled by AWACS planes and balloons, said
Coast Guard Adm. Paul Yost.
   ``Until we have enough of them it will be possible for druggies
to fly around us. The C3I is not going to correct that,'' Yost
said. ``Within the next 12 months we'll double our radars and this
will make a big difference.
   ``It's the most capable air interdiction center in the world,
and if it works the way it's supposed to work, I'll be very
pleased,'' he said. ``But there aren't enough assets in the world
to seal our border to the two to three tons of cocaine that cross
it every week.''
</TEXT>
