<DOCNO> AP890430-0035 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-30-89 1458EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-FusionWars     04-30 0648</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Fusion Wars,0667</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nuclear Fusion Researchers Say Nature's Attack Unjustified</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SALT LAKE CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two scientists who have been taken aback
by attacks on their experimental claims of room-temperature nuclear
fusion have lashed out at the source of the latest rebuff _ the
British scientific journal Nature.
   Fusion researchers B. Stanley Pons and Martin Fleischmann said
the prestigious journal forced them to withdraw their paper and
made inaccurate statements, and that one editor was ``mumbling in
the dark,'' the Deseret News quoted them as saying in Sunday's
editions.
   On March 23, Pons, a chemistry professor at the University of
Utah, and Fleischmann, of England's University of Southampton,
announced that an experiment involving palladium and platinum
electrodes immersed in heavy water had yielded energy indicating
nuclear fusion had taken place. Heavy water is like ordinary water
except that ordinary hydrogen atoms have been replaced by
deuterium, a heavier cousin or isotope of hydrogen.
   Further, the scientists claimed the so-called ``cold fusion''
experiment had yielded more than four times the energy needed to
produce it. Previous attempts at fusion have involved extremely
high temperatures.
   While laboratories around the world have duplicated the
experiment and reported similar results, others have reported
failures and critics have remained unconvinced.
   Nature, in an April 27 edition that contained several articles
on fusion, speculated that the Utah experiment is fatally flawed
and will never be verified.
   ``The Utah phenomenon is literally unsupported by the evidence,
could be an artifact and given its improbability, is most likely to
be one,'' wrote John Maddox, editor of the 120-year-old magazine.
   Pons said Nature had dipped to ``sensationalism of the worst
type. I have never in my life seen such a scandal by a scientific
journal to discredit two people. They have a privileged position
that they are using.''
   Fleischmann criticized Nature's repeated accusations that he and
Pons leaked to reporters their intent to submit to Nature a
scientific paper on their experiments.
   ``At the (March 23) press conference we stated it was quite
incorrect to disclose the the name of the journal we were
submitting to because it would restrict the freedom of action of
the editor,'' Fleischmann said.
   ``It could have only come from other people submitting papers,
or from reviewers or the staff of Nature itself,'' he said. ``I
think it's an impertinence that Nature feels itself entitled to
repeat an allegation which is untrue.''
   They said that on the same day they made their announcement,
they submitted a preliminary paper to Nature and met Nature's
requirements for submission.
   After their researchers' more lengthy scientific paper was
published in the Journal of Electroanalytical Chemistry, Pons said,
Nature requested substantially more information.
   Nature gave them three days to revise and beef up their original
submission at a time when they had heavy speaking and research
obligations, they said.
   ``They forced us to withdraw it by deadlining us and breaking
their own rules,'' Pons said.
   Pons and Fleischmann said they replied in full to questions
posed by reviewers assigned by Nature to read their manuscript,
sending the replies to Nature. They accused the magazine of not
forwarding the replies to the reviewers, though the publication had
accused them of failing to respond to the reviewers' comments.
   ``We did reply. It is they (the editors) who did not send the
replies to the reviewers,'' Fleischmann alleged.
   David Lindley, Nature's assistant physics editor, said there is
frustration in the scientific world because the experiment hasn't
been confirmed, and that Pons and Fleischmann are inaccessible to
researchers.
   ``I can't understand why if they are so certain, they aren't
helping out other people.''
   Pons called Lindley's statements ludicrous.
   ``The editors of Nature have no idea who we have been talking
to, who has seen the experiment, how many people have been given
our data, how many scientists we are collaborating with,'' Pons
said. ``He (Lindley) is mumbling in the dark.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890430-0036 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-30-89 1459EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Japan-USTrade     04-30 0754</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-US Trade,0775</SECOND>
<HEAD>Get Tough With Japan On Trade? Good Luck</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY THORSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An official takes an hour to lay out Japan's
position on a thorny trade issue, then comes to the bottom line on
Tokyo's response to Washington's demand. ``It's impossible.''
   Not all issues between Japan and the United States are that
difficult. The two countries agreed on how to divide the
development and production of a new fighter based on the F-16 for
Japan's air force _ a matter that involves security and technology
issues as well as trade.
   But enough trade issues fit into the difficult-to-impossible
category that this country is braced for a hard time as Washington
decides on using the hammer of the new trade act to cut Japan's $55
billion trade surplus with the United States.
   Virtually simultaneous with President Bush's announcement Friday
of the co-production deal on the fighter, U.S. Trade Representative
Carla Hills hit Japan a double blow:
   _Japan was given more space than any other country in a report
on 34 countries said to have significant barriers to imports from
the United States. The list is to be used to set priorities for
Washington to start intensive negotiations under the 1988 trade act
and eliminate the barriers. Otherwise sanctions may be imposed.
   _In the area of telecommunications equipment, Ms. Hills moved
directly to the verge of sanctions. Charging that Japan had
``failed to live up to all its commitments,'' she declared that
U.S. officials now will consider how to penalize Japanese companies
through higher import duties or other restrictions, Washington
reports said.
   Telecommunications equipment accounts for a big slice of the
U.S. trade deficit. U.S. Commerce Department statistics show a $2.2
billion deficit with Japan in this sector in 1987.
   It was the area described as impossible by Toru Arizono, a
director of the Communications Policy Bureau in the Ministry of
Posts and Telecommunications.
   Interviewed before the U.S. action, Arizono produced U.S.
Commerce Department documents showing Japan as second only to the
United States in permitting foreign companies easy access to the
telecommunications market.
   He said the problem originated solely with the Motorola company,
which he said was ``trying through political means'' to get what it
had been unable to attain in Japan's market for cellular car
telephones.
   ``Other U.S. companies are not submitting anything to us,''
Arizono said. ``If all were complaining, then we would make a
maximum effort to see that there is fair competition among all
companies.''
   Motorola complains that Japan's failure to allocate a frequency
for its car phones in Tokyo blocks the company from access to a
market it estimated as worth $2 billion during the next 10 years.
   Arizono explained that DDI, the Japanese company marketing
Motorola car phones, agreed several years ago to divide the country
with another Japanese firm, which got the Tokyo-Nagoya area while
DDI-Motorola got the rest of the country.
   The problem was that they were using incompatible systems, and
though technical advice was against it, the ministry agreed to the
establishment of two radio systems.
   Motorola-equipped cars from Osaka, however, cannot connect to
the phone system if they come to Tokyo, Arizono said, and so
Motorola wanted a third radio system to accommodate its demands.
   ``There are no radio spectrum resources in the Tokyo area,'' he
said. ``It's impossible.''
   The best Japan could do, he said, was to have Motorola and other
foreign suppliers help to set worldwide technical standards for the
next step in car phones _ digital operation _ so there would be no
problems of interconnection.
   Digital car phones will be coming in a few years, he said.
   The Bush administration wants faster progress in the short run.
Washington's tough line on trade, however, risks a combative
response from Japan.
   Japanese officials reacted sharply to both U.S. trade moves
Friday. Foreign Minister Sousuke Uno said the threat of sanctions
on telecommunications equipment was ``extremely regrettable.'' He
warned that Japan might charge the United States with unfair trade
practices under the world trade pact called the General Agreement
on Tariffs and Trade.
   The minister for international trade and industry, Hiroshi
Mitsuzuka, said in a statement as he departed for trade talks in
Washington that the overall report on import barriers showed U.S.
misunderstanding of Japanese trade policy.
   ``It is very disappointing that our intention has never been
understood by U.S. representatives, despite many bilateral talks,''
Mitsuzuka said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Larry Thorson is Asia news editor for The
Associated Press.
</TEXT>
