<FIRST>r w AM-DolphinDeaths     04-30 0471</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dolphin Deaths,460</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lawmakers Say Pollutants May Have Helped Kill Dolphins</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JANE E. ALLEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government should reopen an investigation
into the deaths of more than 750 bottlenose dolphins on the
Atlantic Coast to determine whether pollutants weakened their
immune systems, say two New Jersey congressmen.
   The most likely cause of the dolphins' deaths was fish tainted
by a naturally occurring neurotoxin, known as brevetoxin, found in
red tide algae swept north from the Gulf of Mexico, said a report
released jointly last week by the National Marine Fisheries
Service, Office of Naval Research and Marine Mammal Commission.
   But it also said brevetoxin was found in tissue samples from
only eight of 17 beached dolphins tested, accounting for fewer than
half of the tested and only a fraction of the 750 who were stranded
on beaches in 1987 and 1988.
   Citing that discrepancy, Reps. Frank Pallone and Rep. Jim
Saxton, D-N.J., backed by environmentalists, urged that the
investigation be reopened.
   ``It is critically important to find out for certain whether or
not water quality or a man-made chemical contributed to the
dolphins' deaths,'' said Saxton.
   A spokesman for the National Oceanographic and Atmospheric
Administration acknowledged the need for more study, but said some
politicians and environmentalists were using the issue to draw
attention to pollution.
   ``There are individuals and groups who have a vested interest in
having man-made pollution be the sole cause,'' said NOAA spokesman
Brian Gorman.
   Brevetoxin does not stay in living tissues after three to five
days, Gorman said, which might account for its absence from some of
the tissue samples.
   The report said ``many questions will remain unanswered until
directed studies are pursued,'' including a look at chronic
exposure to the toxin, a determination of environmental conditions
that led to the deaths and examination of a representative sample
of stranded marine mammals for biological toxins.
   ``Equally important is the need to resolve the growing question
of whether contaminants at levels found in the dolphins might have
affected their resilience and rendered them more susceptible either
to the toxin or the the microorganisms that eventually brought them
to their demise,'' the study said.
   Bruce McKay, a marine biologist with Greenpeace, said the
government report found that tissue from the dead dolphins
contained high levels of PCBs, which are known immune system
suppressors.
   ``The levels overall were among the highest levels ever found in
the marine mammal population,'' McKay said, and could have weakened
dolphin immune systems or compromised the dolphins' abilities to
withstand exposure to compounds such as brevetoxin and bacteria.
   The House Merchant Marine and Fisheries Committee subcommittee
on oversight and investigations has scheduled a hearing May 9 to
hear testimony from the author of the report, Dr. Joseph R. Geraci
of the University of Guelph in Ontario, Canada.
</TEXT>
