<FIRST>r i AM-Thatcher-Polls     04-30 0400</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Thatcher-Polls,0410</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two Polls Show Many Britons Disenchanted with Thatcher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two opinion polls published Sunday indicate
growing public disenchantment with Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher
as she approaches 10 years in power.
   A Harris poll commissioned by The Observer newspaper said 40
percent of the respondents said they would like Mrs. Thatcher to
retire immediately, 8 percent said she should go within a year and
10 percent want her to stand down before the next election.
   Governments are elected for a maximum of five years, so the next
election could be anytime up to 1992.
   Mrs. Thatcher will complete a decade in power Thursday, the
anniversary of when she was first elected Conservative prime
minister. She won re-election in 1983 and 1987.
   Fifteen percent of those questioned said Mrs. Thatcher should
retire within two years after the next election; 13 percent said
five to 10 years from now; and 2 percent by the year 2000. Another
4 percent said Mrs. Thatcher should never retire.
   The newspaper did not account for the remaining 8 percent of
those questioned.
   Two-thirds of the 1,040 people sampled in the April 19-20 poll
said they believe she has ``gone too far with her policies.'' They
cited her reorganization of the National Health Service and tax
cuts for high earners, among other things.
   According to the poll, those questioned said Mrs. Thatcher's
good qualities were, in order, her determination, courage,
strength, leadership and energy. They said her bad qualities were
her voice, uncaring nature, obstinacy, policies and big-headedness.
   A Gallup poll for The Sunday Telegraph, a pro-Thatcher weekly,
said three-quarters of those questioned believe Mrs. Thatcher has
brought about a decline in public services like roads, schools and
public hospitals, while 54 percent thought the phrase ``Thatcher's
Britain'' had derogatory connotations.
   The newspaper gave no details about the size and timing of the
Gallup poll. No margins of error were given for either poll.
   Forty percent of those questioned in the Gallup poll said the
``quality of life'' in Britain had deteriorated in the last decade,
and 75 percent saw a worsening of public services, the poll
indicated. Thirty-two percent believe the quality of life has
improved under Mrs. Thatcher.
   Forty-four percent believe the economy has strengthened under
Mrs. Thatcher, while 35 percent think it has weakened. Seventy
percent approved of labor union laws that make it harder for unions
to stage strikes.
</TEXT>
