<FIRST>r a AM-Obit-Cummings     04-30 0211</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Obit-Cummings,0216</SECOND>
<HEAD>`Seven Brides For Seven Brothers' Producer Dies At 84</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jack Cummings, who started as an office boy
at MGM studios and became a producer of such Hollywood musicals as
``Seven Brides for Seven Brothers,'' has died of heart failure. He
was 84.
   Cummings, who also produced ``Teahouse of the August Moon'' and
``Kiss Me Kate!'' during a 30-year career making films, died Friday
at Cedars-Sinai Medical Center, said family friend Simon Menkes.
   ``He had a spark of life that was unequaled by anybody I ever
met,'' Menkes said. ``He was also a master storyteller. He was not
only a renowned filmmaker, but had a personal magnetism and could
hold people spellbound. He was truly one of Hollywood's finest.''
   Cummings was born in New Brunswick, Canada, and worked his way
from a job as an MGM office boy to script clerk, assistant director
and short subject director-producer before he started producing
feature films in 1934.
   Among his dozens of productions, which included comedies and
dramas as well as musicals, was ``Easy To Wed'' in 1946, one of
Lucille Ball's first comedy roles.
   Cummings is survived by a son, four daughters and three
grandchildren, Menkes said. A memorial service was scheduled for
Monday in Los Angeles.
</TEXT>
