<HEAD>Gramm Renews Call For ``National Crime Emergency''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARTON REPPERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Phil Gramm renewed his call Sunday for
declaration of a ``national crime emergency'' to quickly expand
prison facilities and take other measures to help crack down on
violent crime.
   ``In America today, we have crime without punishment,'' Gramm
said, noting that while 40,000 people were arrested on felony
charges last year in the District of Columbia, only 1,400 of them
went to prison.
   Gramm, appearing on the CBS program ``Face the Nation,''
asserted that no matter what else is done to deal with the root
causes of crime, ``we have got to take violent criminals off the
streets.''
   ``Now what we're trying to do is to build more prisons _ 70,000
more prison beds,'' said the Texas Republican. ``We want a national
crime emergency to allow us to go out on closed military bases,
pitch tents, use temporary buildings, put the violent criminals in
jail and keep them there. And do it now.''
   Rep. Charles Rangel, D-N.Y., said that ``it's absolutely
ridiculous to believe that our first line of defense should be
spending the billions of dollars that we are in building jails,
without being willing to spend millions of dollars in finding out
the reasons why people have this anti-social behavior.''
   Also interviewed on the same program was Peter Reinharz, chief
prosecutor of the Juvenile Court in New York City, where several
teen-agers have been arrested in a brutal attack April 19 on a
28-year-old investment banker while she was jogging in Central Park.
   ``It's evident that the juvenile justice system, as it presently
stands, has no deterrent effect whatsoever in light of the
increasing nature of the violence and the increasing severity of
the crimes we've seen over the last several years,'' Reinharz said.
   He said that for juvenile offenders ``there's very little threat
of jail. So maybe that's one of the things that has to change in
order to bring about some sort of deterrent value.''
   Reinharz said he also was particularly concerned about ``the
increase in sex crimes among the very young.''
   ``We have 8-year-olds, 9-year-olds, 10-year-olds committing
forcible rape, forcible sodomy, aggravated sexual abuse,'' he said.
</TEXT>
