<FIRST>r a AM-BabyDeath     04-30 0586</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Baby Death,0603</SECOND>
<HEAD>Baby's Doctor Says Father Deserves Lenience For Death Of Comatose
Child</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAULINE JELINEK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The family of a comatose baby who died after his
father disconnected his respirator made funeral preparations
Sunday, and the child's doctor said there had been no hope the
infant's condition would have improved.
   Sixteen-month-old Samuel Linares, who had been comatose since
swallowing a balloon last August, died Wednesday. Police said his
father held off hospital workers at gunpoint, tearfully unhooked
the child's respirator and held him until he died.
   Rudy Linares, 23, of west suburban Cicero, faces a first-degree
murder charge. He is free on $75,000 bond.
   Linares said he did it ``because I loved my son ... I love my
wife.'' The funeral was planned for Monday.
   Linares' act revived an ethics debate over whether medicine
should merely prolong life, and it stirred a storm of opinions
about laws governing hopelessly injured or sick children.
   It prompted an outpouring of calls from parents whose children
have died. Though many said they were disturbed by Linares'
methods, most said they sympathized with the emotions that drove
him.
   Even the boy's doctor, Dr. Gilbert Goldman, director of the
pediatric intensive care unit at Rush-Presbyterian-St. Luke's
Medical Center, said mercy should be used in dealing with Linares.
   ``I kept telling the dad, `I know it's terrible, but it won't
last much longer,''' Goldman said.
   ``Sammy wasn't dead, but he couldn't get better,'' he said.
   ``He remained highly unstable the first week or two, but then he
stabilized,'' Goldman said. ``Tests showed he was no longer at risk
of immediate death. He had brain activity but it was clear he would
not live outside a chronic vegetative state.''
   ``I sincerely hope the dad will not be punished for this action
although it was against the law,'' the doctor added. He also said
he hoped new legislation would result from the incident, to make
law catch up to technological advances.
   In 1988, there were some 100,000 ``technology-dependent''
children, through age 18, meaning they require some medical device
to keep them alive, not always in hospitals, according to the
National Association of Children's Hospitals and Related
Institutions of Alexandria, Va.
   Susan Maher said she can identify with Linares. Her daughter,
Elizabeth, spent the first two years of her life at the University
of Illinois Hospital in Chicago, the victim of cerebral palsy and
chronic lung disease. Ms. Maher says there were times she
considered unplugging Elizabeth's life-support equipment.
   ``A lot of times there is hardly anybody else in the hospital
unit,'' she said. ``You could do it. It enters your mind when you
feel you're being selfish by making a child suffer.''
   Ms. Maher didn't do it and Elizabeth, now 7, lives with the aid
of a ventilator.
   Cynthia Kramer of Calumet City lost her 13-year-old son, David,
to leukemia last December.
   David had developed a lung infection and was on a respirator,
and the hospital asked his parents on Christmas Eve to give
permission to let him die.
   ``His dad and I said we wanted everything to stay on until
David's very last heartbeat _ we didn't want to play God,'' said
Ms. Kramer. ``When God says `Come on,' that's when you come on. He
died on Christmas Day.
   Unlike Lenares' comatose baby, she said, ``David was dignified
and he was brave and he was a fighter and he was an alert,
intelligent person. You don't think about doing that to a person
like that.''
</TEXT>
