<FILEID>AP-NR-04-30-89 1616EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-TankerSpill     04-30 0712</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Tanker Spill,0733</SECOND>
<HEAD>State Wants Exxon To Push Harder In Oil Spill</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL JENKINS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VALDEZ, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Alaska environmental officials said Sunday
they are frustrated by the pace of oil spill cleanup efforts in
Prince William Sound and are pressuring Exxon to be more aggressive.
   At the same time, a newspaper reported that a company Exxon
hired for the cleanup is scaling back its work force at Seward,
outside the sound.
   The giant oil company has promised to clean more than 300 miles
of shoreline in the sound by Sept. 15, but some people are
skeptical.
   Monday is Exxon's deadline for providing the state with a plan
for waste disposal and cleaning of Gulf of Alaska shorelines hit by
the drifting oil.
   The 987-foot tanker Exxon Valdez rammed Bligh Reef on March 24,
spilling nearly 11 million gallons of heavy North Slope crude oil
as fishermen prepared for their upcoming seasons and migrating
animals and birds headed into the sound.
   Colleen Burgh, shoreline cleanup coordinator for the Alaska
Department of Environmental Conservation, said the company should
be experimenting with new clean-up techniques and bringing them to
the state for evaluation.
   ``We get the impression they are sitting back and waiting for us
to tell them which method to use,'' she said Sunday. ``They've been
working two weeks and they don't even have a mile clean.''
   ``They've got to get more aggressive if they're going to get the
job done,'' said Burgh.
   Asked if she was skeptical Exxon could meet its Sept. 15
deadline, Burgh said that ``using the methods I've seen to date,
I'd have to say yes.''
   In a letter to Exxon, the state said the company should examine
all cleanup methods and let state and federal agencies decide
whether they should be used. Burgh said she could envision use of
bulldozers to redo the contours of beaches in some cases.
   The state letter was addressed to Andy Teal, part of Exxon's
shoreline advisory panel. He said his company was working to make
the cleanup more efficient and had been talking with state
officials.
   ``We've had a number of discussions as to enhancing the
operations out there,'' Teal said. ``That letter came as a bit of a
surprise to me. Those discussions were already taking place.''
   He said the company was bringing in new equipment for trials.
During the weekend, crews on Smith Island experimented with the use
of increased water temperatures to remove oil, he said.
   Meanwhile, the Anchorage Daily News reported the oilfield
services company Exxon hired to carry out the cleanup is scaling
back its work force at Seward because of self-proclaimed success in
saving Resurrection Bay, outside Prince William Sound and opening
onto the Gulf of Alaska on the eastern end of the Kenai Peninsula.
   Plans called for about 100 workers in Seward to be put on
rotating schedules Sunday, working one week and taking the next off
without pay. The scheduling change by Veco International Inc. will
halve the number of people on the job on any day, the newspaper
said.
   ``We are not laying off anyone, we're putting them on
rotation,'' said Ron Rolan, general supervisor of Veco's Seward
operations.
   Exxon has said that by midsummer as many as 4,000 people will be
hired to scrub oiled shores.
   Work crews in Prince William Sound mostly have been plugging
away on Naked, Smith and Seal islands, using methods that include
wiping oil off rocks by hand, flushing beaches with cold salt water
and blasting oil with hot water.
   On heavily oiled Smith Island, workers have been inching their
way down a boulder-strewn shore toward an area seals use for
pupping.
   ``The cold water, even at high pressure, cannot get the oil
up,'' said Bill Lamoreaux, the state cleanup coordinator. ``You
have to change methods as you go.''
   The state estimates Smith Island has three miles of heavily
oiled shoreline and a half-mile of beach with moderate oil
contamination.
   There are more than 30 other islands on the cleanup list, some
with more than 50 miles of heavily oiled shoreline.
   Burgh said none of Smith Island's shoreline has been cleaned to
the state's satisfaction. ``There's an incredible amount of oil on
Smith Island. They're going to be there for a while.''
</TEXT>
