<FIRST>r i AM-Senegal-Mauritania     04-30 0376</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Senegal-Mauritania,0389</SECOND>
<HEAD>Airlift Returning Refugees to Uncertain Future</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFFREY ULBRICH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NOUAKCHOTT, Mauritania (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Transport planes Sunday
repatriated thousands of refugees between Senegal and Mauritania in
an effort to halt violence between people of the neighboring
nations.
   On Sunday, 12 Mauritanians were killed in Touba, 125 miles east
of Dakar, Senegal, sources said. There were no reports of
anti-Senegalese attacks in Mauritania.
   The sporadic violence against expatriate Senegalese and
Mauritanian communities in both countries began last month in a
dispute over border land between the two west African nations. More
than 200 people are thought to have died in the fighting.
   A dusk-to-dawn curfew declared Tuesday in Nouakchott remained in
effect but in Dakar, a 10 p.m. to 6 a.m. curfew failed to stop
scattered pillaging of Mauritanian shops.
   French, Spanish and Morrocan planes carried 5,000 refugees
between the capitals on Sunday, officials said on condition of
anonymity. A total of 3,000 Senegalese and 5,000 Mauritanians have
been repatriated since the airlifts began late Saturday, officials
said.
   An estimated 20,000 Mauritanians were being held under army
protection at a fairground outside Dakar, awaiting a flight home.
About 6,000-7,000 Senegalese were harbored by the Mauritanian Red
Crescent at a Nouakchott mosque and an exhibition hall.
   Nouakchott airport, surrounded by soldiers and armored vehicles,
became a virtual military base as civilian and military planes
loaded Senegalese for the trip home. Lines of refugees could be
seen walking under military escort to one of six Moroccan planes
Sunday.
   At the fairground in Dakar, customs officials and police
confiscated everything from knives to money and jewels from
Mauritanians preparing to depart, according to Agence
France-Presse. Customs officers told the French news agency they
were ordered to do so and said Senegalese leaving Mauritania were
getting the same treatment.
   Senegal President Abdou Diouf appealed late Saturday for calm
despite what he called the ``inhuman and degrading treatment'' of
Senegalese citizens in Mauritania. That was an apparent reference
to a two-day bloody outburst on Tuesday and Wednesday in which
Senegalese were said to have been mutilated by Mauritanians.
   Diouf, in a radio and television broadcast, said Mauritania
sparked the spiraling violence, which began April 9 when two
Senegalese were killed in a border dispute over grazing land.
</TEXT>
