<FIRST>r i AM-WestGermany-Iran     04-30 0132</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-West Germany-Iran,0135</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Denies Iranian Charges of Espionage</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   West Germany on Sunday strongly denied
charges by an Iranian newspaper that its diplomats in Tehran are
spies.
   ``The government vigorously denies these allegations,'' said
Foreign Ministry spokesman Hanns Schumacher.
   An Iranian newspaper on Saturday called for the expulsion of
West German diplomats from Tehran, calling them ``diplomats
disguised as spies,'' for alleged involvement in a U.S. espionage
network.
   Schumacher refused to comment on details of the Iranian
newspaper editorial.
   West Germany recalled its ambassador from Tehran in February to
protest Iranian leader Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini's calls for the
death of British novelist Salman Rushdie. Khomeini said Rushdie
blasphemed Islam in his novel ``The Satanic Verses.''
   Schumacher said ``about a dozen'' embassy staff members remain
in Tehran.
