<FILEID>AP-NR-04-30-89 1642EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Mass-AcidRain 1stLd-Writethru a0670 04-30 0466</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mass-Acid Rain, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0670,0474</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dukakis Launches Acid Rain Offensive</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Boston Harbor, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 8 grafs to recast, moving up description of rules
as toughest of any state. Picks up 7th graf pvs, `The program...'. Deletes
last graf pvs, now redundant.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MILTON, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Michael S. Dukakis announced new
anti-acid-rain rules billed as the toughest in the nation, making
good a 1985 vow to implement in-state regulation if the federal
government failed to act.
   The governor made his announcement Saturday at Houghton's Pond,
one of hundreds of Massachusetts bodies of water threatened by acid
rain. New state emissions limits will take effect at the end of
1994, but plans for meeting them must be submitted by Jan. 1, 1991.
   ``We are hoping our action will encourage Congress to adopt a
tough set of national standards and will encourage other states to
take similar action,'' he said in a statement. ``The future of our
lakes, our forests and our natural resources depend on it.''
   New Hampshire, New York and Wisconsin are among several states
that have already implemented acid rain regulations, but none has
as yet mandated controls as stringent as those for Massachusetts,
officials said.
   Acid rain is caused by combustion of fossil fuels in power
plants and motor vehicles, which release sulfur and nitrogren
oxides into the air.
   About 25 percent of acid rain in Massachusetts comes from
in-state sources with the remainder coming from the Midwest and
other sources, according to government figures.
   The new program includes limits on sulphur dioxide emissions
from 168 factories and power plants in Massachusetts.
   Officials predict it should result in an annual reduction of
between 68,000 and 87,000 tons of sulphur dioxide emissions _ about
a 20 percent to 25 percent cut in the 370,000 tons of sulphur
dioxide currently emmitted from all sources in Massachusetts.
   The program gives companies several options in reducing
pollution. They can conserve energy, switch to natural gas or
cleaner fuels, or earn credits by making greater reductions in one
part of their operation while leaving another part dirtier than
otherwise allowed.
   Studies have shown 185 Massachusetts rivers, ponds and streams
are already acidified and 800 more bodies of water will be affected
in the next 40 years unless action is taken to curb emissions,
officials said.
   Environmentalists hailed the new regulations.
   ``This represents a landmark victory for the environment and
public health,'' said Jenny Carter, environmental attorney for the
Massachusetts Public Interest Research Group.
   A spokesman for Boston Edison Co., one of the state's largest
utilities, said the impact the new restrictions was not yet clear.
   ``We knew it was coming down but it's a little too early to
assess the impact on Edison,'' Bill Connolly said. ``We'll have to
wait and see.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
