<FIRST>r i AM-Vietnam-MIAs     04-30 0230</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Vietnam-MIAs,0236</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Experts Complete MIA Investigation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Six U.S. military experts returned to
Bangkok on Sunday after working with Vietnamese officials to
resolve the fates of missing American soldiers, a U.S. Embassy
spokesman said.
   The spokesman, Ross Petzing, said the experts divided into two
teams and searched areas of southern Vietnam, but he had no details
of the findings.
   Petzing said they had arrived in Vietnam on April 12 with a
four-man forensic team.
   While the six experts journeyed south for the search, the
forensic team stayed in the capital of Hanoi to examine remains
that the Vietnamese earlier found. The forensic team left Vietnam
on April 22.
   It was the fifth joint investigation aimed at resolving the
fates of 1,730 Americans listed as missing in action in Vietnam.
Previous joint investigations were limited to about 10 days each.
   During the projects, the investigators interview villagers who
witnessed crashes of U.S. warplanes.
   On Thursday, Vietnam returned 21 sets of remains that it
believes may be those of missing Americans. U.S. military personnel
picked up the remains in a ceremony at Hanoi airport and flew them
to Honolulu for analysis.
   That brought to 184 the number of remains Vietnam has returned
since August 1987, when it agreed to speed up work on the issue in
exchange for Washington's help in encouraging private humanitarian
aid to Vietnam.
</TEXT>
