<FIRST>r w AM-Shoreham     04-30 0829</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Shoreham,790</SECOND>
<HEAD>The Shoreham License: Symbol of Nuclear Rebirth or Industry Failure?</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KIM I. MILLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Shoreham nuclear power plant is about to
have its plug pulled without generating a usable kilowatt for Long
Island, but that didn't stop the Nuclear Regulatory Commission from
giving an operating license to the controversial reactor.
   The commission acted with full knowledge the Long Island
Lighting Co. is hoping to rid itself of the $5.5 billion albatross
in exchange for life-sustaining rate hikes and a
multibillion-dollar tax writeoff.
   Some industry-watchers have called awarding the license the
NRC's last, best attempt to salvage anything from a plant whose
name connotes everything cited as going wrong with the nuclear
power industry _ construction delays, fraud, huge cost overruns,
safety problems and endless federal red tape.
   Others hailed it as evidence of a pumped-up NRC, which, backed
by the new administration, will shepherd in a new nuclear age.
   And some said it was an attempt by the NRC to deflect pointing
fingers when Shoreham is laid to rest and Long Islanders experience
their next brownout.
   ``I think the NRC did not want to be blamed for having a corpse
on its own doorstep,'' said James Schlesinger, energy secretary in
the Carter administration, now an analyst at the Center for
Strategic and International Studies.
   NRC Chairman Lando Zech has declined to interpret the
commission's action, or to concede that Shoreham's license may have
been the culmination of a long, expensive and ultimately academic
exercise.
   ``We have acted, in my view, very responsibly,'' Zech said April
20, after the commission voted 4-0 to award the license. ``We
wouldn't authorize it to operate if we didn't think it could
operate and if we didn't think it could operate safely.''
   Shoreham's orchestrated demise cannot be completed until LILCO
shareholders sign the death warrant, which they are expected to do
in a vote sometime in mid-June. Last year, the shareholders
approved a buyout, but that deal crumbled when the state
legislature refused to do likewise by a Dec. 1 deadline.
   The next step will be for a state agency to buy the plant for a
symbolic dollar and the New York Power Authority would oversee its
decommissioning and dismantling. In return, LILCO gets annual rate
hikes of approximately 5 percent for a decade, keeping the utility
afloat and guaranteeing Long Island the highest electric rates in
the country.
   But Zech has intimated that the transfer of Shoreham's license
may not be a foregone conclusion, saying the action ``would be a
very formal process,'' complete with hearings and public comment.
   One government agency expected to offer its opinion is the
Department of Energy, which lately has been threatening to create
roadblocks to the transfer.
   However, Schlesinger said the current energy secretary, James
Watkins, has no power to stop it.
   ``He can register his views with the NRC but I think the NRC
appears to have charted its course,'' Schlesinger said.
   Peter Bradford, New York Public Service Commission chairman and
former chairman of the NRC, also discounted DOE's clout in the
Shoreham case.
   Indisputably, the Shoreham case and similar problems at the
Seabrook, N.H. plant drove the NRC to reclaim powers it had
sacrificed to the states after the accident at Three Mile Island on
March 28, 1979.
   When the state and local governments blocked the Shoreham and
Seabrook licenses by refusing to participate in emergency planning,
the NRC changed its regulations. Thus, Shoreham is the first plant
to be licensed based on a utility-created evacuation plan which
assumes that in the event of an emergency, state and local
authorities will cooperate.
   The NRC also streamlined the process for getting a reactor built
and started, passing a regulation that would allow the NRC to award
an operating license at the same time as it approves plant
construction. Part of that ruling also calls for the
standardization of plant design.
   But no utility has ordered a nuclear plant since 1978, and all
those ordered after 1974 have been canceled.
   ``Those rule changes are a complete waste of time,'' said
Bradford. ``Nuclear power's fundamental problem right now is that
it just can't compete economically with the other supply sources
and conservation and in the bidding systems that more and more
states are looking to screen their power supply in the future.''
   But Loring Mills, vice president for nuclear activity at the
Edison Electric Institute, a utilities trade association, predicted
a nuclear renaissance, with the next nuclear plant order coming
sometime between 1994 and 1999.
   Kenneth Alvin Solomon, a nuclear scientist with the Rand Corp.,
a California-based think tank, predicted a turnaround in the
nuclear industry, ``hopefully, in my lifetime.''
   ``The alternatives to nuclear reactors are not necessarily all
that attractive all the time,'' he said. ``Oil plants, coal plants,
have pollution. Oil is something that we have to depend on other
countries for, so there's a whole series of reasons that I see the
picture getting better.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
