<FIRST>r a AM-Bicentennial-NY 1stLd-Writethru a0672 04-30 0581</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bicentennial-NY, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0672,0589</SECOND>
<HEAD>At Bicentennial, Bush Hails Washington's Vision</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf to clarify that hall is not the original. SUBS
grafs 5-6, bgn `After the...,' with 3 grafs to CORRECT that Bushes left
for heliport, sted airport, UPDATE with color on parade. Picks up 7th graf
pvs, ```It's so...'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Bicentennial, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY10</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BILL STIEG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Americans marked 200 years of the presidency
Sunday with a re-enactment of George Washington's inauguration, a
tribute from his 40th successor, prayers for a few more stable
centuries and, of course, a parade.
   ``It was Washington's vision, his balance, his integrity, that
made the presidency possible,'' President Bush told a crowd outside
Federal Hall National Memorial, in lower Manhattan, after actors
re-enacted the first president's inauguration in 1789. The building
is an 1842 structure on the site of the original hall.
   As he finished his speech, hundreds of red, white and blue
balloons were released into the sky from behind Federal Hall, and
multicolored confetti, streamers and even flowers rained down from
30 stories up in neighboring skyscrapers.
   Bush earlier prayed in Washington's pew and stood beside a
Washington stand-in during the re-enactment of the oath-taking,
which climaxed a week of festivities in New York from fireworks to
symposiums, and in a sense, ended 13 years of bicentennial bashes
that began in 1976.
   After the ceremony, Bush and the first lady, Barbara, briefly
took their place in an inaugural parade, but headed off to the
heliport at the end of Wall Street.
   That left the parade to the other George, as portrayed by actor
William Sommerfield, who gestured grandly to the crowds that lined
Broadway.
   The parade was a thumping, blaring stream of military bands,
fife and drum corps and marchers in colonial dress. Bands from all
four military service branches marched _ a first, organizers said _
along with a police bagpipe band and a kazoo band.
   ``It's so easy to take for granted that we have a democracy,''
said one of the onlookers, Chris McCarthy, 29, of New York.
``Something like this drives home the fact that we've had it for so
long.''
   ``There is a sense of history _ the Constitution lives,'' said
Joan Marshall-Dutcher of King of Prussia, Pa., whose husband, David
Dutcher, played Washington's aide in the re-enactment.
   The day began with a service at St. Paul's Chapel of Trinity
Church, where the Bushes sat in the pew used by Washington after
his inauguration, held when New York City was the nation's capital.
In his sermon, Episcopal Bishop Paul Moore reflected on the
nation's future as well as its past.
   ``It was a review of the events that got us here, but also about
the people left out _ those with AIDS or crippled by poverty and
ignorance, for example,'' said Sen. Frank Lautenberg, D-N.J. ``It
was very moving.''
   A huge stadium-style television screen alongside the red, white
and blue platform gave viewers close-ups of the ceremony, in which
Sommerfield, as Washington, solemnly took the oath of office,
laying his hand on the same Bible used in 1789.
   Sommerfield then delivered excerpts from Washington's Inaugural
Address, which in reality was not spoken to the crowd but to
Congress inside the hall.
   Sunday's clear weather contrasted to the heavy overcast
Saturday, when smallish crowds watched a flotilla of ships in the
afternoon _ including the aircraft carrier USS Forrestal _ and
partially fogged-in fireworks at night.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
