<FIRST>r a AM-Bradley-Finances     04-30 0477</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bradley-Finances,0498</SECOND>
<HEAD>Probe Of LA Mayor's Finances Widens</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   City officials plan to broaden an
investigation into Mayor Tom Bradley's financial dealings and his
ties to a city-funded task force that hired his daughter,
newspapers reported Sunday.
   Investigators have interviewed some city officials as many as
eight times about the newly re-elected mayor's links to Far East
National Bank, and in coming weeks will examine his relationships
with Valley Federal Savings &amp; Loan Association and the task force,
the Los Angeles Times reported Sunday.
   The newspaper cited unidentified sources in City Attorney James
Hahn's office.
   Hahn is expected to testify Wednesday before the City Council's
Governmental Operations Committee on the status of his
investigation.
   ``We will subpoena everyone involved if we have to,'' said
Councilman Nate Holden, who came close to forcing Bradley into a
runoff in the April 11 election.
   Bradley will not comment until Hahn's investigation is
completed, said Bill Chandler, a mayoral spokesman.
   During appearances Saturday, Bradley refused to discuss
allegations that he was paid to serve on the boards of Far East and
Valley Federal while they did business with the city.
   The mayor also denied knowledge that his daughter, Phyllis
Bradley, 43, was hired by the Task Force for Africa-Los Angeles
Relations.
   ``I knew nothing about it, had nothing to do with it,'' Bradley
said. ``She's entitled to conduct her own life and to seek her
employment wherever she wishes.''
   Bradley's daughter was a task force secretary for almost 10
months in 1985 and 1986, said Chandler.
   The task force, which works to improve African business and
cultural ties with the city, is headed by Juanita St. John, with
whom Bradley has real estate investments, the Times said.
   At least twice since 1985, Bradley has intervened to ensure
funding of about $98,000 a year for the task force, despite City
Council objections, the Los Angeles Herald Examiner reported Sunday.
   Hahn, and reportedly the Police Department, are also looking
into Bradley's advisory work for Far East, which earned him $18,000.
   Far East President Henry Hwang told the Los Angeles Times in an
interview Friday that Bradley was the only one of 46 bank advisory
board members who was paid. He said Bradley was considered helpful
to the bank on foreign trade issues.
   Bradley has denied knowing that the bank was doing business with
the city at the time he served as a consultant.
   The mayor, who resigned from the advisory board last December,
said he was unaware of the bank's municipal ties until the issue
was raised during his re-election campaign last month. He has since
returned the $18,000.
   But court documents indicated he made at least two inquiries to
city departments on behalf of the bank last year.
   Bradley also received at least $150,000 while serving on the
board of directors of Valley Federal Savings &amp; Loan Association.
</TEXT>
