<FIRST>r a AM-BushPapers 1stLd-Writethru a0631 04-30 0547</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush Papers, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0631,0558</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bidding Begins for Bush Library</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf, `Bush was ..., to CORRECT that Bush was born
in Mass., sted Conn.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   George Bush's administration has just begun, but
Texas universities and his alma mater, Yale, already are squaring
off for the chance to be the home of his presidential library.
   It has the trappings of any good political fight: cities
battling for prestige and a piece of history _ not to mention
revenues from an estimated 400,000 annual tourists. In Bush's case,
the battle is all the more interesting since he has divided
loyalties and familial ties.
   Bush was born in Massachusetts and educated in Connecticut, but
has claimed Texas as home for more than 40 years. That opens the
bidding among several of Texas' finest and Bush's Ivy League alma
mater, Yale.
   ``He's spoken on the campus many times. We just feel that this
is very much a part of his home,'' said Mimi Crossley, a
spokeswoman for Rice University in Houston. Bush has had a ``long
history of involvement'' with Rice, she said, mentioning a
one-semester teaching job he held in 1978 and friendship he has
with Rice officials and supporters.
   Besides, she said, Rice promotes its academic excellence _ only
fitting for a president's papers.
   But so does Yale.
   Jack Siggins, Yale's deputy librarian, said that about four
years ago a Yale professor contacted then-Vice President Bush about
donating his papers to the New Haven, Conn., school, where Bush
graduated in 1948. ``He didn't make a commitment,'' Siggins said.
   Shortly after the November election, Yale repeated its offer,
and the Texas universities chimed in. Both Rice and University of
Houston representatives have written letters to Bush about being
the library site, but Texas A&amp;M is mounting the most ambitious
offensive.
   A&amp;M grad Michel Halbouty, a longtime Bush friend, broached the
matter to Bush after the election, and last week A&amp;M announced a
detailed battle plan to capture the library, including a steering
committee to prepare the bid and the enlistment of graduate
students to help design the building.
   ``I'm flattered (at A&amp;M's interest) and it may be what I want to
do,'' Bush recently told Newsweek. ``The idea has great appeal to
me.''
   But he also cited Rice as a ``logical'' location. At any rate,
he said, ``It's a little premature, but I want Texas to be the
recipient.''
   Both Rice and Houston are touting their Houston location over
the A&amp;M Aggies site at College Station, about 80 miles northwest of
Houston. But A&amp;M officials say College Station lies equidistant
from several metropolitan areas, which would allow it to draw at
least 500,000 visitors a year.
   William McKenzie, chairman of A&amp;M's board of regents, made
another point, saying in a news release that Texas A&amp;M is
``philisophically'' compatible with the conservative Bush.
   Back East, Yale isn't sitting on its hands. Siggins said the
university will quietly pursue the Bush library with the force of
persuasive logic.
   Among other selling points, Yale has a region in which Bush's
family goes back for centuries, impressive collections and scholars
and experience at finding donations.
   ``Let me just say that there's a lot of time. A lot of things
can happen,'' Siggins said. ``You never can tell.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
