<FIRST>r a AM-Obit-Dudarew-Ossetynski     04-30 0161</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Obit-Dudarew-Ossetynski,0169</SECOND>
<HEAD>Polish-Born Writer-Director-Actor Dies at 78</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leonidas Dudarew-Ossetynski, an
internationally known director, actor and drama teacher who
co-authored ``To the Actor,'' has died of cancer. He was 78.
   Dudarew-Ossetynski died Friday at the West Los Angeles Veterans
Hospital.
   A graduate of the National Academy of Drama in Warsaw, he came
to the United States in 1941 after service in the Polish army.
   In Los Angeles, Dudarew-Ossetynski worked with famed
actor-director Michael Chekhov to write ``To the Actor'' and he
taught the Chekhov Method to drama students at his Ossetynski
Actors Laboratory on Melrose Avenue.
   Among his productions was ``Matka,'' which he staged in 1983 at
the Cast at the Safe Harbor theater.
   Earlier, Dudarew-Ossetynski performed on stages throughout the
United States and Canada and directed several Off Broadway plays.
   His movie credits included ``Walk Don't Run,'' ``The Man in the
Glass Booth'' and ``Alias Mike Fury.''
   Dudarew-Ossetynski leaves a daughter, Valerie Hunken, and two
granddaughters.
</TEXT>
