<FIRST>r a AM-TransplantInvestigation 1stLd-Writethru a0703 04-30
0551</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Transplant Investigation, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0703,0565</SECOND>
<HEAD>Justice Department Drops Investigation of Starzl</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS lead to include allegation that foreigners paid more. SUBS
8th graf, `The Pittsburgh...,' with 3 grafs to UPDATE with comment from
newspaper.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal prosecutors have dropped a grand jury
investigation into whether pioneering transplant surgeon Thomas
Starzl gave high-paying foreigners preferential treatment at two
hospitals here.
   The Justice Department told the Philadelphia office of the U.S.
Department of Health and Human Services in a letter Friday that
investigators had decided not to bring a case against Starzl, said
Judy Holtz, spokeswoman for the social agency's inspector general's
office.
   ``We have no other comment,'' she said.
   The investigation, which lasted nearly three years, followed a
Pulitzer Prize-winning series of reports by The Pittsburgh Press on
transplants by surgical teams headed by Starzl.
   Starzl, the chief of transplantation at the University of
Pittsburgh School of Medicine and head of transplant programs at
Presbyterian-University and Children's hospitals, said his
reputation and that of the hospitals had been cleared.
   ``It's just a clean bill of health,'' he said.
   However, the surgeon said he did not feel vindicated by the
government's action. ``I never really felt beleaguered by the whole
thing, because I knew the stories weren't true,'' he said.
   Madelyn Ross, managing editor of The Pittsburgh Press, defended
the newspaper's series.
   ``It's not a newspaper's job to determine criminality. That's
somebody else's job like the U.S. attorney, and I can't speak for
what his investigation turned up.
   ``But I can speak for what The Pittsburgh Press research showed,
and it showed a clear and demonstrable inequity in the transplant
system. We stand by that information.''
   According to the newspaper's 1985 report, medical records showed
that about 28 percent of the transplants by Starzl's team from
January 1984 to May 1985 were for foreigners who often were not as
ill or had not waited as long as other patients on waiting lists.
   The Press found that foreigners who received kidneys paid four
times more in surgeon's fees than Americans who got the same
operations.
   The federal grand jury began taking secret testimony in August
1986.
   Health and Human Services Inspector General Richard Kusserow had
asked officials to investigate whether a Pittsburgh center violated
the National Organ Transplant Act, which prohibits selling organs
for profit.
   Kusserow had not named which hospital or surgeon was being
investigated until Friday.
   In its transplant series, the Press said the Starzl team
bypassed hospital policy to ensure that foreign patients received
kidney transplants quickly.
   The policy said donor organs should go ``to locals first,
hard-to-match patients second and then, foreign nationals,'' former
chief of surgery Dr. Henry Bahnson told the newspaper in 1985.
   Following the newspaper's report, transplant surgeons under
Starzl said they would allocate only 5 percent of the slots on
kidney waiting lists to foreigners.
   The hospitals also established an adivsory committee to review
how patients are selected for transplants and designed a point
system that assigns priorities to waiting patients.
   Starzl said Friday that one of the reasons foreigners were
billed differently than U.S. citizens was that they didn't medical
and private insurance.
   ``I'm not a bill collector, and that whole part of the operation
does not concern me,'' he said. ``I am not in a fee-for-service
business.''
</TEXT>
