<FIRST>r a AM-UMW-Jackson     04-30 0538</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-UMW-Jackson,0559</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jackson Rallies Striking Mine Workers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID REED</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WISE, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Rev. Jesse Jackson encouraged striking coal
miners Sunday to continue non-violent civil disobedience to force
concessions from Virginia's biggest coal company, saying ``we will
not surrender.''
   ``This is a great moment in which we have come together,''
Jackson told about 10,000 Pittston Coal Group workers and United
Mine Workers union supporters who flooded the Wise County
Fairgrounds.
   ``The tradition of Martin Luther King Jr. and John L. Lewis have
come together,'' Jackson said, referring to the slain civil rights
leader and the militant former UMW president. ``The spirit cannot
be defeated.''
   The two-time Democratic presidential candidate wore a camouflage
outfit, which strikers have adopted as a uniform to make themselves
harder to identify.
   About 1,700 UMW members went on strike April 5 against Pittston,
Virginia's largest coal company, after working without a contract
for 14 months.
   Last week, the strikers began blocking roads and entrances to
mines and a coal processing plant. The non-violent strategy has led
to 1,182 arrests, an impromptu rally that sealed off a downtown
area and a walkout by 220 students at two local high schools.
   UMW president Richard Trumka on Sunday promised to keep the
strike going.
   ``We're exercising our right to strike, to protect our families
and we will not go back,'' Trumka said as rain poured onto the
fairgrounds.
   Minutes later, as Jackson was about to speak, the rain stopped.
   In addition to strikers and their families, the rally drew UMW
members from around the region and members of other unions. About
7,000 people packed the fairgrounds, and another 3,000 listened to
speeches through loudspeakers outside. A few sheriff's deputies and
state troopers monitored the rally and directed traffic.
   Earlier, Jackson addressed an overflow crowd of about 350 people
at First Baptist Church in Big Stone Gap, about 30 miles southwest
of here.
   ``You're fighting for your jobs, for worker safety. ... You're
in pain but do not panic,'' Jackson said. ``We don't know how long
the strike will last, but we will not surrender.
   ``We do not want any violence, but we do want job security and
justice,'' he said.
   The union has accused Pittston officials of acting unfairly
during contract talks and trying to break the UMW by refusing to
negotiate in good faith.
   Pittston officials have denied those accusations, and have said
the contract proposed by the UMW, which the other major eastern
coal producers have signed, would threaten the company's stability.
   The major sticking points in the talks are pension and health
benefits, according to UMW officials.
   Trumka said the UMW would continue following its civil
disobedience strategy next week. He said it would continue beyond
the Virginia coal fields, but refused to be more specific.
   Jackson and Trumka said they would soon visit Japan to ask steel
industry officials there to stop buying Pittston coal until the
strike is settled. Pittston is the largest U.S. supplier of
metallurgic coal to Japan, Trumka said.
   Trumka also said that the UMW had formed a coalition with the
Australian Confederation of Mine Workers, and that Australian coal
company officials had agreed not to fill Japanese orders not filled
by Pittston.
</TEXT>
