<HEAD>Inmate Released From Jail Back In the Clink Less Than An Hour Later</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man freed from jail under a court order to
relieve overcrowding was behind bars within an hour of his release
on charges of attempted armed robbery.
   Ronnie Fisher, 30, was released from the Fulton County Jail at
9:40 p.m. Friday, according to Lt. John Eubanks, assistant watch
commander at the jail.
   Thirty-five minutes later, a police officer saw Fisher chase a
man and knock him to the ground, according to a police report.
Fisher was arrested, and at 10:35 p.m. was admitted to the Atlanta
Pretrial Detention Center.
   Fisher, who had been held previously on theft and drug charges,
was one of 263 prisoners released Friday and Saturday to comply
with an order from U.S. District Judge J. Owen Forrester, who set a
ceiling of 1,781 inmates for the jail.
   Fisher's victim said he was attacked after refusing to give
Fisher a dollar for beer. The two had met on a bus.
   Officials have expressed concern the released prisoners might
turn to crime even though the inmates have been provided with
transit passes and money to help tide them over.
