<FIRST>u i AM-Britain-Shooting 2ndLd-Writethru a0696 04-30 0819</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-Shooting, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0696,0842</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gunman Kills One, Injures 14 in Shooting Spree</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS grafs 6-17, `Ten-year-old...shouting anything' with 16
grafs to UPDATE with more witness quotes. Pick up 18th pvs, `Grant said...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WHITLEY BAY, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man dressed all in black and armed
with a shotgun went on a 15-minute shooting spree Sunday in a
northeastern coastal town, killing one man and injuring 14 people
before being arrested, officials said.
   Police were questioning the man to determine the motive for his
rampage in Monkseaton, about a mile from the Whitley Bay seaside
resort and 250 miles northeast of London.
   The gunman, who was not identified, roamed the streets shooting
at anyone he saw, including one person in a car, another on a
bicycle, one in a garden and one outside a church, said a spokesman
for a local ambulance service.
   ``There must have been about 12 different locations given where
this man had gone round,'' said Ken Heads, superintendent of the
Northumbria ambulance service. ``He was having a go at any person
he met.''
   Witnesses said the gunman was dressed all in black, with dark
sunglasses and his hair in a pony tail. They said he wore an
ammunition belt around his waist and prowled the streets for 15
minutes, pausing only to shoot.
   Ten-year-old Ryan Boyd told the British Broadcasting Corp. TV
News:
   ``Across there on the corner there was this man ... all dressed
in black from head to foot. He started walking around here with the
gun. He was all sturdy, rigid. He wasn't frightened or anything, he
was just running around with his gun from side to side shooting
people.''
   Police later said the man they arrested was a 22-year-old from
Whitley Bay. They did not give his name.
   After the shooting spree, he drove to a pub, where authorities
seized him without any gunfire, police said. Detective
Superintendent Bob Benton said the suspect's vehicle contained a
loaded shotgun, cartridges, and a hunting knife.
   Speaking at a news conference, Benton said the arrested man was
not believed to have known personally any of the people he shot.
   The first emergency call came at 12:01 p.m., Heads said. Two
shots were fired at the ambulance as it arrived, and the crew had
to dive for cover, he said.
   A second ambulance was dispatched, and within three or four
minutes the service was inundated with calls reporting a gunman on
the loose and people lying injured in the streets, he said.
   Within seven minutes, five ambulances from Whitley Bay and
nearby Newcastle upon Tyne and North Tyneside were on the scene.
The first crew to arrive found a man lying dead in a street, Heads
said.
   North Tyneside Hospital spokesman Michael Scargill said 14 men
and women were treated for gunshot wounds. He said six were
hospitalized and eight were sent home.
   Police identified the dead man as Kenneth Mackintosh, 41, a
telephone company employee who was married and had two children.
   The Rev. Tom Grant said parishioners leaving his midday service
at St. Andrew's United Reformed Church heard a shot and saw a woman
fall to the ground opposite their church.
   Parishioner Angela Bartle, 45, said the injured woman was
conscious ``and saying `help me,' but I had to leave her lying
there'' because the gunman, 150 yards away, had reloaded his gun
and was aiming it at her.
   Mrs. Bartle said the gunman ``looked very calm. He wasn't
shouting anything.''
   Eric Holloway, 47, said he and his wife and son were in their
car when they saw the gunman load his shotgun and point it toward
them. ``I shouted to my wife, who was driving, to duck down,''
Holloway said.
   ``Then a Ford Granada came up behind and the man driving that
car took the shot intended for us. When he got out of his car he
was screaming with pain.''
   ``He just kept on re-loading and I could see he was experienced
at handling the gun because of the speed with which he did this.
There was no time to get to him while he was re-loading because he
did it so quickly,'' he said.
   Grant said the gunman fired about four shots, then took off in a
vehicle as police officers approached.
   ``We were all so surprised. It was all over in about 15 minutes
so there was no panic or anything, but for a time we didn't believe
it.''
   Britain's worst shooting incident occurred in August 1987, when
Michael Ryan went on a rampage in the town of Hungerford, west of
London, killing 16 people, including his mother, before turning his
gun on himself.
   Britain's already strict gun control laws were then tightened to
outlaw, among other things, semiautomatic rifles like the one Ryan
used.
   The blood bath shocked Britain, where most police are unarmed
and the people believe their society to be relatively free of
violence.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
