<SECOND>AM-Quayle, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0675,300</SECOND>
<HEAD>Vice President Scuba Dives and Plays Tennis Before Heading To Indonesia</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDs: SUBS 2nd graf to CORRECT spelling of Indonesian vice president's
name. Single name is cq.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOAN MOWER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President Dan Quayle arrived here
on the second leg of his Southeast Asian trip Sunday, poised to
deal with the issues of trade and Cambodia.
   Quayle, who spent most of Sunday scuba diving in the Great
Barrier Reef off Australia's northeast coast, paid a courtesy call
on Vice President Sudharmono after his evening arrival.
   Quayle and his wife, Marilyn, delayed their departure from
Australia for about an hour so they could play another round of
tennis.
   On Monday, the vice president is to hold talks with Indonesian
officials which were billed as get-acquainted sessions.
   Some of the trade concerns Quayle is expected to broach concern
patent protection and intellectual property.
   The vice president may also raise human rights issues,
particularly the status of East Timor, a former Portuguese colony
annexed by Indonesia in 1975.
   Human rights groups say Jakarta has failed to account for
thousands of missing people killed in custody in East Timor.
   An important diplomatic meeting will be Quayle's session with
Prince Norodom Sihanouk, the former leader of Cambodia who is
supported by the United States in his drive to run the country once
the Vietnamese occupation troops withdraw this fall.
   Sihanouk is in Jakarta to see Hun Sen, head of the Vietnamese
puppet government in Cambodia.
   Washington is considering giving military assistance to the
non-communist groups.
   Quayle has said the United States is adamantly opposed to seeing
the Khmer Rouge, the group that killed over a million people in
Cambodia 1975-1978, return to power.
   On Tuesday, Quayle heads for Singapore and Thailand, the last
stops on his 12-day trip before he heads home.
</TEXT>
