<FILEID>AP-NR-04-30-89 2023EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Broadcasters     04-30 0397</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Broadcasters,380</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cronkite to Lead Campaign Aimed Against `Ravaging of Free TV'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAY ARNOLD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LAS VEGAS, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former CBS newsman Walter Cronkite will
kick of a campaign aimed at keeping the nation's TV sets from being
turned into ``vending machines'' for the pay TV industry, a
broadcasters' group said Sunday.
   The public _ and broadcasters _ have taken free TV for granted
as cable TV and VCRs increasingly eat into the audiences for
sports, news and entertainment programs, said Milton Maltz,
chairman of the Free TV Task Force of the National Association of
Broadcasters.
   The result, he said, will be that viewers will have ``to pay for
what they once got for free through the American system of
broadcast television,'' Maltz told an appreciative audience at the
NAB convention here.
   ``The pay TV industry is a financial creature born by deal
makers and bred on junk bonds,'' Maltz said. ``Local stations are
under attack by cable operators who can decide to drop a station or
change a station's channel location at will.
   ``The ravaging of free TV, however, has yet to begin in
earnest,'' Maltz said.
   He said the chairman of a major cable TV operator told him that
at some point broadcasters will be paying to have their signals
carried on cable systems.
   Maltz said sports on free TV were an endangered species and an
owner of a National Football League team had told him the NFL's
plan was ``to make every TV receiver an extension of the stadium
box office.''
   ``I wouldn't be surprised that in his mind he could visualize
every set as the equivalent of a program vending machine,'' Maltz
said.
   ``Indeed, he could probably even hear the machine crying out
every half hour `Feed me, feed me' as the viewer obliges by
stuffing more dollars in the slot,'' Maltz said.
   He urged the broadcasters to act to make the public ``aware of
the danger facing our institution of free TV.''
   Cronkite's message will appear within the next two months
simultaneously on prime time in every TV station in the country,
Maltz said, to launch the Free TV campaign, which also will include
additional on-air promotions by local stations.
   ``The issue is simple,'' Maltz said. ``Is the future pay TV or
is it free TV? There is room _ there is need _ for both.''
</TEXT>
