<FILEID>AP-NR-04-30-89 2108EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Paraguay-Elections     04-30 0566</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Paraguay-Elections,0590</SECOND>
<HEAD>Opposition Warns Of Irregularities, Governing Party Anticipates Victory</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED McCULLOUGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ASUNCION, Paraguay (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Opposition leaders warned of voting
irregularities Sunday as Paraguayans prepared to vote in the freest
elections in decades.
   Polls predict that Gen. Andres Rodriguez, who led a coup Feb. 3
to oust the dictatorship of Gen. Alfredo Stroessner, will win up to
70 percent of the vote in Monday's elections.
   However, Rodriguez's closest challenger, longtime opposition
leader Domingo Laino of the Authentic Radical Liberal Party, has
told voters that they could be risking ``a Stroessner system
without Stroessner.''
   ``We are conscious that we are participating in elections that
are marked by flaws, but we're doing it becuase we want a peaceful
transition, not a violent one,'' Laino said Sunday.
   Fernando Vera, the top candidate of the Revolutionary Febrerista
Party, openly predicted Rodriguez and the Colorado Party would win
the presidency and control of congress, and worried that his party
could not even be sure its ballots would be available at every one
of the more than 10,000 voting tables nationwide.
   ``We've distributed our ballots to the main places, but I`m not
sure we've gotten through'' to smaller, more remote villages across
this California-sized South American republic of 4 million, he said.
   The parties are responsible for printing and distributing their
own ballots.
   Rodriguez insists that Monday's voting will be fair. Voters will
cast ballots in private, and their right index finger will be
dipped in indelible purple ink afterward to prevent double voting.
   The general told an international election observer on Sunday,
``Do you like soccer? Well, in a soccer game, the team that loses
usually blames the referee, the lineman and the conditions of the
field.''
   Rodriguez was one of Stroessner's closest aides before bringing
down the 34-year-long regime and taking over as provisional
president. Rodriguez also belongs to the Colorado Party, which has
controlled the government for 42 years.
   Voters also will pick 36 senators and 72 deputies to fill all
the seats of the two legislative chambers.
   The winning party is awarded two-thirds control of congress. The
other parties will split the remaining seats.
   Eight parties, including many banned under Stroessner, have
fielded slates of candidates.
   The main issue of the campaign has been who can best promote
democracy in this country that has never known it. Many Paraguayans
have concluded that Rodriguez, who controls the army and enjoys
great personal prestige, is as good a choice as any.
   Rodriguez has pledged to build democratic government, restore
human rights, and allow freedom of the press.
   However, Laino has urged Paraguayans to choose a complete
political housecleaning rather than ``to continue the Stroessner
system with a few new names.''
   Laino has said his party will pull out of any government that
does not reform the constitution, electoral law and penal code.
   Even many Laino supporters doubt he can win.
   Only the Colorados are likely to have ballots at virtually all
the 10,000 voting tables nationwide.
   The Colorados have dominated the airwaves with commercials.
   They are also most likely to benefit from a bloated, outdated
voter registration list of 2.2 million. Even election officials
acknowledge it may carry 600,000 names too many.
   Voting is obligatory for Paraguayans ages 18 to 60. Polls open
at 7 a.m. (7 a.m. EDT) and close at 4 p.m. (4 p.m. EDT). Unofficial
results are expected late Monday night.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
