<FIRST>r i AM-Brazil-Elections     04-30 0299</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brazil-Elections,0308</SECOND>
<HEAD>Brazil's Governing Party Selects A Centrist Candidate</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRASILIA, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Centrist Ulysses Guimaraes defeated a
progressive opponent Sunday to win the presidential nomination of
the governing party at the end of a turbulent convention.
   The selection is considered the formal opening of the campaign
for the country's first direct presidential election in 29 years.
The vote is scheduled for Nov. 15.
   The members of the Brazilian Democratic Movement Party picked
Guimaraes, a 72-year-old federal congressman and former party
president, over Waldir Pires, governor of the northeastern state of
Bahia. Pires was the choice of the party's progressive wing.
   Some influential party members put up strong resistance to
Guimaraes, arguing instead for a younger, more vigorous figure to
contest the challenge posed by increasingly popular left-wing
candidates.
   The Democratic Movement Party is the country's largest, thus
making Guimaraes a serious contender in the election.
   However, political analysts give the party a slim chance of
sweeping the election, as it has done in past polling. They say it
is associated with the failures of President and party member Jose
Sarney, who has been unable to stop 1,000 percent annual inflation
and reverse public disenchantement with traditional politics.
   Guimaraes' opponents in the race include centrist reformer
Fernando Collor de Mello, governor of the poor northeastern state
of Alagoas. He is forming a new party.
   Other contenders are left-wing populist Leonel Brizola, former
governor of Rio de Janeiro state and a member of the Democratic
Labor Party; and federal Congressman Luis Inacio Lula da Silva of
the Workers Party, a socialist group.
   Brazil returned to civilian rule under Sarney in 1985 after 21
years of military rule. However, Sarney took office after an
electoral college vote controlled by the military regime.
   Under the constitution, he cannot run for re-election.
</TEXT>
