<FIRST>r a AM-RobotRetrieved     04-30 0220</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Robot Retrieved,0226</SECOND>
<HEAD>Robot Retrieved, but Not Yet Returned to Service.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of high school students will join an
underwater expedition to a Spanish galleon in the Mediterranean Sea
via camera and satellite Monday. But an understudy is taking the
star robot's place.
   The robot Jason, retrieved Saturday after it broke loose from
its tether and sank in the Mediterranean, will be completely
evaluated before being returned to service, said Woods Hole
Oceanographic Institution spokeswoman Sonya Hagopian.
   ``Jason will probably be going back in, but not right away,''
Hagopian said Sunday. ``It could be a matter of just a few days.''
   The robot Medea, which helped find the lost robot, will take
Jason's place when the first of 250,000 students in 13 U.S. and
Canadian cities hook up with marine explorers led by Robert Ballard
via two-way satellite. The galleon is located off the Italian coast.
   About 2,000 museum officials, teachers and technicians were
testing the system last week when Jason, a propeller-driven
submersible equipped with video cameras and maneuverable arms,
disappeared overboard and sank about 2,100 feet.
   Jason, a newer version of the robot Ballard used to examine the
wreck of the Titanic in the North Atlantic, appeared to have
sustained only minor cosmetic damage, Hagopian said.
   The expedition is scheduled to end May 14.
</TEXT>
