<FIRST>r a AM-CarCrash 1stLd-Writethru a0723 04-30 0429</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Car Crash, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0723,0439</SECOND>
<HEAD>PRECEDE Oak Forest, Ill.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eleven Die in Auto Wrecks in Illinois, Georgia</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES throughout with Georgia wreck, police comment on Illinois
wreck; no pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A car collided with a tractor-trailer in a Georgia downpour
Sunday, killing six people, and five more died in Illinois when
their station wagon veered off an interstate and into the base of a
sign. Seven of the dead were children.
   Four other children were injured, three critically, in the
accident near Oak Forest, Ill., and two people were hurt in the
wreck in Forsyth County, Ga., officials said.
   The Illinois crash occurred at 6:15 a.m. when the southbound
station wagon, packed with seven children and two adults, ran into
the base of an Interstate 57 exit sign, said Capt. George Hopman of
the Markham Fire Department, which helped in the rescue.
   The driver, Michael Gates, 41, his wife, Mattie Davis, 28, and
their son Ivory Davis, 5, were all dead on arrival at hospitals in
Oak Forest, a suburb south of Chicago. All were from nearby
Kankakee.
   Two other children _ Athyid Swapsy, 3, and Riquisha Banks, 8 _
were dead on arrival at South Suburban Hospital in Hazel Crest,
said spokeswoman Lynn Foster. Yachiyl Swapsy, 2, was in fair
condition there, Ms. Foster said.
   Yeroubbaal Swapsy, 4, and Shalmon Sanford, 7, were in critical
condition with multiple injuries at Olympia Fields Osteopathic
Medical Center, police said.
   A seventh child, identified as Tamar Swapsy, 5, was in
``extremely critical'' condition with multiple traumas at
University of Chicago Hospital, said spokeswoman Carol Eck.
   Authorities did not know the relationship between the couple and
the other children.
   ``According to eyewitness reports, the car just started drifting
slowly to the right,'' said State Trooper J.K. Howell.
   Alcohol or drugs were not a factor, Howell said. Police said
none of the victims appeared to be wearing seat belts.
   The Georgia accident occurred during a torrential downpour
around 2:40 p.m. near Lake Sidney Lanier, almost 30 miles northeast
of Atlanta, according to State Patrol Cpl. Mike Nash.
   The car was coming down a hill and around a curve on Georgia 20
when the driver ``evidently lost it and got over in front of the
tractor-trailer,'' Nash said. The truck rolled over the car.
   None of the victims' names were released because one of the four
dead children could not be identified, Nash said. Authorities
believed she was being watched for the weekend by one of the adults
in the car and her parents were out of town.
</TEXT>
