<FIRST>u i AM-Japan-USSubmarine 2ndLd-Writethru a0730 04-30 0320</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-US Submarine, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0730,0327</SECOND>
<HEAD>Three U.S. Sub Crewmen Fall Into Sea, Two Missing</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS thruout with official confirmation, details of accident.
No pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three crewmen on a U.S. Navy submarine fell
overboard Monday when a wave swept the vessel as it conducted
surface operations in waters off Japan's southwestern island of
Kyushu, and two remained missing, U.S. military officials said.
   One of the men who fell from the 2,145-ton Barbel was rescued
later, the U.S. Forces Media Liaison Office said in a statement.
   It said the rescued man was picked up by the submarine itself
after a search aircraft spotted him. His identity and condition
were withheld.
   The submarine was conducting surface operations in international
waters when a wave swept away the crewmen, who were standing watch
on deck, the statment said.
   Kiyoshi Harada, spokesman for Japan's Maritime Safety Agency,
said the accident occurred about 31 miles southwest of Noma Cape in
Kagoshima Prefecture, or state.
   Harada said three Japanese aircraft and four vessels, including
three Japanese patrol boats, were searching for the two missing men.
   A Japanese defense official, who spoke on condition of
anonymity, said that before the accident, the submarine surfaced
because it was taking on water from a hatch. He refused to
elaborate.
   However, Lt. Jeff Gradeck, a Navy spokesman based in Yokosuka,
denied that report. ``We have no information that there is anything
wrong with the Barbel, and it is taking part in the search,'' he
said.
   In Washington, Defense Department spokesman Maj. John Smith said
he had heard reports of the missing men but he had no further
details.
   There were no reports of injuries of any other crewmen.
   The Barbel, built in 1956 and equipped with 6 torpedo tubes, has
a crew of 77, according to U.S. military officials.
   The 219-foot-long, diesel-electric powered Barbel belongs to the
last non-nuclear combat submarine class built by the Navy.
</TEXT>
